'%s' is specified multiple times in '%s' of '%s'
data.cause: The specified value is specified multiple times.
data.action: Remove duplicates and retry.

data.message: Update to attribute AGENT_FILENAME is not currently supported. Please recreate the resource type with new value.
data.cause: Attempt was made to update AGENT_FILENAME attribute.
data.action: Delete existing resource type and add it back with the new value.

data.message: Failure threshold exhausted for resource '%s'
data.cause: The resource instance has failed more times than allowed in\nthe specified time interval. It will not be restarted automatically.
data.action: Please identify and fix the problem. Restart the resource\nmanually thereafter.

data.message: Server '%s' is not in any of the server pool(s) hosting resource '%s'
data.cause: An attempt was made to start a resource on a server that is\nnot currently an active server in any of the resource's server pool(s).
data.action: Use a server name that is currently an active server of the\nresource's server pools(s).

data.message: Server '%s' is not a hosting member of resource '%s'
data.cause: An attempt was made to start the resource on a server not\nlisted as a hosting member of the resource.
data.action: Use a server name that is listed as a hosting member.

data.message: Failed to update server pool '%s'. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Could not update repository with server pool details.
data.action: Use the ocrcheck utility to detect errors in OCR. If problems exist, the registry may need to be recovered or restored.

data.message: Resource '%s' may not be started on server '%s' because the server is not in either '%s' or '%s' server pools
data.cause: The resource's placement policy only allows it to run in\nthe specified server pools. An attempt was made to start it on a server\nassigned to a different pool.
data.action: Either use a different server or set the value of\nSERVER_POOLS to *, which will allow the resource to run on any server.

data.message: '%s' is a resource alias for '%s' and cannot be updated
data.cause: An attempt was made to update a resource as if it were\na resource.
data.action: Please update the resource which this alias refers to\ninstead.

data.message: '%s' is a resource alias for '%s' and cannot be unregistered
data.cause: An attempt was made to unregister a resource alias as if it\nwere a resource.
data.action: Either unregister the resource which this alias refers to\nor modify its ALIAS_NAME attribute to not have a resource alias.

data.message: The instance of resource '%s' may only run on '%s'; check on '%s' is unnecessary
data.cause: A check was issued on a server for a resource instance that may only\nrun on a particular server.
data.action: Please issue a check on the server where the resource instance is\nsupposed to be run.

data.message: No instance of resource '%s' found on '%s'
data.cause: A check was issued on a server for a resource which does not have any\noffline instances and no running instances on that server.
data.action: Please issue a check on a server where a resource instance\nmight be running.

data.message: Modifications to the built-in resource type '%s' are not allowed
data.cause: An attempt was made to modify a built-in resource type.
data.action: Modification of built-in resource types is not allowed.

data.message: User %s does not have permission to operate on resource %s.
data.cause: Access control list on the resource do not permit the user\nto operate on the resource.
data.action: Access privileges on the resource must be honored or this\nuser must be given appropriate permissions.

data.message: Invalid permissions specified for access control.
data.cause: Access permissions are specifies using 'r', 'w', 'x' and\n'-' characters to indicate read, write and execute permissions. '-'\nindicates no access of any kind.
data.action: Check format for the permissions string and re-run the\ncommand with the correct string.

data.message: Acl entry '%s' has been specified more than once.
data.cause: Access permissions for the entry have been specified\nmore than once.
data.action: Specify permissions for each entry only once and rerun the\ncommand.

data.message: A resource type with the name '%s' is already registered
data.cause: A resource type with such name is already registered.
data.action: Use a unique name for the new resource type.

data.message: Attribute '%s' cannot be overridden for a resource type
data.cause: An attribute was specified that is not allowed in a resource type.
data.action: Do not use the attribute specified in the error message for a\nresource type.

data.message: Resource '%s' depends on resource '%s'
data.cause: An attempt was made to unregister a resource that is\nreferenced by another resource in the dependency specification(s).
data.action: Either remove the reference to this resource or the other resource\nfirst. Alternatively, the operation can be retried with a force option.

data.message: Resource '%s' is already running on server '%s'
data.cause: The resource is already running on the server; relocate is impossible.
data.action: Select another server.

data.message: Resource '%s' is already starting on server '%s'
data.cause: The resource is currently starting on the server.
data.action: Wait for the request to complete.

data.message: Failed to stop all required resources on '%s'; the server will be restored into the original server pool(s)
data.cause: In order to successfully relocate a server, all resources\nthat cannot run in the new server pool(s) must be stopped. That did not happen and thus the server\nwas placed back into the its original server pool(s).
data.action: Manual intervention in stopping resources is\nrequired. The operation can be retried thereafter. Alternatively,\nanother server can be used.

data.message: Failed to stop all required resources on '%s'; the server will stay in RECONFIGURING state
data.cause:
In order to successfully relocate a server, all resources
that cannot run in the new server pool(s) must be stopped. Since that did
not happen, the server will be kept in the RECONFIGURING state
until the resources that did not stop have been stopped or
unregistered.
data.action: Manually stop the resources that did not stop or\nunregister them.

data.message: The operation requires relocating resource '%s' from server '%s'
data.cause: The operation would end up relocating the resource and the\nforce option is not specified.
data.action: Add more servers to the cluster, stop or relocate the\nresource, or use the force option for the same command.

data.message: The operation requires stopping resource '%s' on server '%s'
data.cause: The operation would end up stopping the resource and the\nforce option is not specified.
data.action: Add more servers to the cluster, stop or relocate the\nresource, or use the force option for the same command.

data.message: Unable to register server pool '%s' as this will affect running resources, but the force option was not specified
data.cause: One or more running resources would be affected by the operation.
data.action: Add more servers to the cluster, stop or relocate the\nresources mentioned right before this error, or use the force option for the same command.

data.message: Unable to modify server pool '%s' as this will affect running resources, but the force option was not specified
data.cause: One or more running resources would be affected by the operation.
data.action: Add more servers to the cluster, stop or relocate the\nresources mentioned right before this error, or use the force option for the same command.

data.message: Unable to relocate server '%s' as this will affect running resources, but the force option was not specified
data.cause: One or more running resources would be affected by the operation.
data.action: Add more servers to the cluster, stop or relocate the\nresources mentioned right before this error, use a different server, or use the force option for the same command.

data.message: Failed to relocate server '%s' to server pool '%s'. The server has been restored to original server pool(s).
data.cause: In order to successfully relocate a server, all resources\nthat cannot run in the new server pool(s) must be stopped. That did not happen and thus the server\nwas placed back into the its original server pool(s).
data.action: Manual intervention in stopping or unregistering resources is\nrequired. The operation can be retried thereafter. Alternatively,\nanother server can be used.

data.message: A value must be specified for attribute '%s'
data.cause: The attribute was not given a value.
data.action: Provide a value and retry.

data.message: The update of resource '%s' would lose track of one or more running instances
data.cause:
An attempt was made to modify the configuration of the
resource such that one or more currently running instance will be
lost track of (the new configuration would change the resource to
have fewer instances).
data.action: Stop the resource and resubmit.

data.message: Unable to register resource '%s' as this will affect running resources, but the force option was not specified
data.cause: One or more running resources would be affected by the operation.
data.action: Add more servers to the cluster, stop or relocate the\nresources mentioned right before this error, or use the force option for the same command.

data.message: crsctl query     - query service state
Unable to modify resource '%s' as this will affect running resources, but the force option was not specified
data.cause: One or more running resources would be affected by the operation.
data.action: Add more servers to the cluster, stop or relocate the\nresources mentioned right before this error, or use the force option for the same command.

data.message: Unable to relocate server %s because it results in violation of a pool %s constraint
data.cause: The requested move was rejected because it would cause either the source or target pool (or both)\nto violate a pool size constraint, as indicated.
data.action: Either change the pool size constraint(s) to accommodate your intent with this move, or\nchoose a different server to move.

data.message: Cannot act on the instance of resource '%s' which is last known to have run on '%s' where Cluster Ready Services are not properly functioning
data.cause:
The resource had been running on the server in the past but currently there's no way to know
if it's still running there because the Cluster Ready Services daemon does not appear to be
running on the server. To prevent possible configuration violation,
any attempt to start the resource instance on another server is rejected.
data.action:
The underlying problem preventing Cluster Resource Services on the server from
functioning properly must be addressed. Only then the resources that used to run there
can be operated on again. Alternatively, the server may be shut down or the clusterware stack
on it stopped completely.

data.message: Server reconfiguration has failed to stop resources '%s' on server '%s'. Resources that did not stop must be stopped or unregistered manually. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The specified resources could not be stopped.
data.action: Stop the specified resources manually using and retry the last action.

data.message: Failed to stop resource '%s' during server reconfiguration on server '%s'.
data.cause: The specified resources could not be stopped.
data.action: Stop the specified resources manually and retry the last action.

data.message: A write of OCR server data '%s' failed. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Could not persist data to OCR.
data.action: Use the ocrconfig and ocrcheck utilities to detect errors in OCR. If problems exist, the registry may need to be recovered or restored.

data.message: Cardinality violation detected on server '%s', resource '%s' is in unexpected state. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The specified resource was in an unexpected state.
data.action: Manually restart the resource.

data.message: Cannot create new resource, the resource type '%s' is not supported. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The specified resource had an incorrect base type.
data.action: Check the attributes for the resource and add it using crsctl again.

data.message: Unable to write event sequence number to OCR. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Could not update OCR with event sequence number.
data.action: Use the ocrconfig and ocrcheck utilities to detect errors in OCR. If problems exist, the registry may need to be recovered or restored.

data.message: Timed out waiting for the server pools to be unfrozen.
data.cause: Timed out while waiting for a client to unfreeze the pools it froze.
data.action: If the problem persists, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Unable to change locks for a running operation '%s'. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: This is an internal error.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Error reading type definition for type '%s'. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: This is an internal error.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Invalid tag for command '%s'. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: An invalid command was received by the CRS daemon.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Command '%s' timed out waiting for response from the resource '%s'. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Timeout occurred while waiting for response to specified command.
data.action: Check that the server targeted by the command is online and responsive.

data.message: Resource '%s' is in an unknown state.
data.cause: Unable to determine the current state of specified resource.
data.action: Manually restart the resource.

data.message: Failed to read repository key for NLS language '%s'. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The key for the specified language could not be read from OCR.
data.action: Use the ocrconfig and ocrcheck utilities to detect errors in OCR. If problems exist, the registry may need to be recovered or restored.

data.message: Policy engine failed to initialize internal types. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Error during initialization of internal data.
data.action: If the problem persists, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Resource '%s' has failed on server '%s'.
data.cause: The specified resource was no longer running.
data.action: The resource will be automatically brought back online. Use crsctl to confirm that it is online.

data.action: None.

data.action: Fix the underlying cause of resource failure and manually restart the resource.

data.message: Maximum restart attempts reached for resource '%s'; will not restart.
data.cause: Specified resource had been restarted too many times.
data.action: Change the maximum restart parameter of the resource, and restart it manually.

data.cause: This is an internal error.

data.cause: Error occurred during registration callback of new resource.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.cause: This is an internal error.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.cause: Internal error in CRS Policy Engine.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Internal error, invalid server '%s' in local placement policy. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Internal error in CRS Policy Engine.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.cause: Could not update repository with resource details.
data.action: Use the ocrcheck utility to detect errors in OCR. If problems exist, the registry may need to be recovered or restored.

data.message: The command may not proceed when Cluster Ready Services is not running
data.cause: This command must stop Cluster Ready Services-managed\nresources. However, Cluster Ready Services is not running, which\ndoes not mean its resources are not running.
data.action: The underlying reason for Cluster Ready Services not\nrunning needs to be resolved and the command retried.\nAlternatively, the command can be retried with the force option.

data.message: Shutdown is already in progress for '%s', waiting for it to complete
data.cause: Another shutdown command was issued for the indicated server in the\npast and it is currently in progress. This command will wait until\nthe original command completes and then complete as well.
data.action: None.

data.message: State change received for resource '%s' from unexpected server '%s'. Details at '%s' in '%s'.
data.cause: A state change was reported for an instance of the resource from a server where the resource was never started.
data.action: Shutdown the resource on the unexpected server

data.message: Failed to shut down resource '%s' on '%s'
data.cause: Shut down failed because the listed resource failed to stop.
data.action: Error message(s) preceding this one should have the details about the\nresources that refused to shut down. Either manually stop those\nresources or retry with the force option.

data.message: Cannot start resource '%s' as it is already in the INTERMEDIATE state on server '%s'
data.cause: An attempt was made to start a resource that is already in the INTERMEDIATE state.
data.action: Determine why the resource is in the INTERMEDIATE state based on the value of the STATE_DETAILS\nattribute. If it is due to a check timeout, no action is needed. Otherwise, manual intervention\nis required to bring the resource out of the INTERMEDIATE state.

data.message: No instance of the resource '%s' should be running
data.cause: An attempt was made to relocate resource and the resource's\ninstances to be relocated have TARGET=OFFLINE.
data.action: Restart the resource to change the value of the TARGET attribute to ONLINE.\nExamining the value of the INTERNAL_STATE attribute can be used to determine if the instances\nare being operated on currently.

data.message: Purging events not published within 15 minutes
data.cause: The events could not be published to the Event Manager Daemon either because it is down or there are errors doing the publish.
data.action: Check the status of the Event Manager Daemon.

data.message: Attribute '%s' has already been declared in a derived type '%s'
data.cause:
An attempt was made to add a new attribute definition to a
resource type that has an identically named attribute already
defined in one or more derived types. Attributes declared in base types can be overridden
in derived ones, but the opposite is not allowed.
data.action: Pick a different attribute name or delete the derived\ntype(s), resubmit, and then add derived types back.

crsctl get css <parameter>\\n    Displays the value of a Cluster Synchronization Services parameter\\n\\n    clusterguid\\n    diagwait\\n    disktimeout\\n    misscount\\n    reboottime\\n    priority\\n    logfilesize
crsctl get css ipmiaddr\\n    Displays the IP address of the local IPMI device as set in the Oracle registry.
crsctl get hostname\\n    Displays the host name
crsctl get nodename\\n    Displays the node name
crsctl get {css <parameter>|hostname|nodename}

crsctl set css <parameter> <value>\\n    Sets the value of a Cluster Synchronization Services parameter\\n\\n    diagwait\\n    disktimeout\\n    misscount\\n    reboottime\\n    priority\\n    logfilesize
crsctl set css ipmiaddr <ipmi_ip_address>\\n    Set the IP address of the local IPMI device in the Oracle registry.
crsctl set css ipmiadmin <ipmi_admin_name>\\n    Set the administrative login for the local IPMI device in the Oracle registry.
crsctl set css votedisk {asm <diskgroup>|raw <vdisk>[...]}\\nwhere\\n    diskgroup       Voting disk diskgroup\\n    vdisk [...]     One or more blank-separated voting file paths

crsctl unset css <parameter>\\n    Unsets the value of a Cluster Synchronization Services parameter, restoring its default value\\n\\n    diagwait\\n    disktimeout\\n    misscount\\n    reboottime\\n    priority\\n    logfilesize
crsctl pin css -n <node1>[...]\\n Pin the nodes (make leases non-expiring).
crsctl unpin css -n <node1>[...]\\n Unpin the nodes (allow leases to expire).

data.message: Unable to access an IPMI device on this system\\n
data.cause:
A test for the availability of an IPMI device failed.  This can
occur if:
- the IPMI device driver is not installed,
- the installed device driver is not supported by Oracle,
- IPMI is not supported on this platform or operating system,
- no IPMI device is present, or
- an IPMI device is present but not configured.
data.action: Verify that IPMI hardware supporting IPMI version 1.5 or greater\nis present and supported on this server, that the IPMI device is\nconfigured and the device driver is properly installed.

that the clusterware stack is down on all other nodes to ensure
data integrity.  A CSS daemon was detected on another node,
so the CSS daemon on this node is terminating.

action is required, otherwise stop the Oracle clusterware
stack that is running on the indicated node. The name and number
of the active node may be unknown.

data.message: Cluster Ready Services is online in exclusive mode
data.cause: Cluster Ready Services is limited to providing internal\nservices to other Oracle Clusterware components. External\nCluster Ready Services are not available.
data.action:
When in exclusive mode, Oracle Clusterware components are
dedicated to the repair or reconfiguration of the Oracle
Cluster Registry, voting files or both.  Oracle Clusterware
should be down and remain down on every other cluster node.
Only commands that check or stop the stack, interact with
Cluster Synchronization Services or aid in Clusterware repair
or reconfiguration should be issued.

data.action: Use srvctl to re-create vip or scanvip specifying an IP address\nwhich is not being used in the network and retry the operation.

data.message: Unable to automatically select a network interface which has subnet mask %s and subnet number %s
data.cause: The subnet mask and subnet number configured for the resource did not\nmatch the subnet mask and subnet number of any network interface on\nthis node.
data.action: Provide a subnet mask and subnet number which matches at least one\nnetwork interface's subnet mask and subnet number using srvctl remove and add\nvip and retry the operation.

data.message: Cannot remove the primary IP %s from the network interface
data.cause: The primary IP of the network interface was incorrectly configured as\nthe VIP.
data.action: Use 'srvctl remove' and 'srvctl add vip' or 'srvctl remove' and\n'srvctl add scan' to provide the correct IP address for the VIP and\nretry the operation.

data.message: Invalid attribute value: %s for the network interface
data.cause: The network interface value did not match the\nsubnet mask and subnet number of any network interface on the node.
data.action:
Modify the network interface's value such that the subnet mask and
subnet number matches the subnet mask and subnet number of at least one
network interface on the node using 'srvctl remove' and 'srvctl add vip' and
retry the operation.

data.message: The VIP address %s does not belong to the subnet %s
data.cause: The VIP's subnet number and the network interface's subnet\nnumber did not match.
data.action: Make the VIP's subnet number match the network interface's\nsubnet number using 'srvctl remove' and 'srvctl add vip' or 'srvctl remove'\nand 'srvctl add scan' and retry the operation.

data.message: Agent timed out waiting for a response from the DHCP server
data.cause:
Agent and the DHCP server were not able to communicate with
each other. Common causes of this failure are due to the DHCP server not
running, or improper DHCP server configuration, or the DHCP server
running out of DHCP leases.
data.action: Identify the cause of the problem from the DHCP server\nlog files. If the problem is due to the DHCP server running out of leases,\nincrease the number of addresses which can be served by the DHCP server.

data.cause: The following error occured during the resouce action.
data.action: Examine the accompanying error messages and respond accordingly.\n

data.message: %s Removed unused HAIP route:  %s / %s / %s / %s
data.cause: A potentially conflicting route in the same subnet as the HAIP\naddresses was found and removed to prevent routing conflicts.
data.action: Validate that the route described was not actually in use.

data.message: All OCR locations are on ASM disk groups [%s], and none of these disk groups are mounted. Details are at \\"%s\\" in \\"%s\\".
data.cause:
OCR was configured on ASM disk groups, and all of the listed
disk groups failed to mount.
The possible causes are:
1. A disk was not accessible.
2. A disk  in a normal or high redundancy disk group failed after the
most recent dismount.
3. The ASM_DISKSTRING in the SPFILE or the GPnP profile was incorrect.
data.action:
Check the ASM alert logs for more information.
To correct disk access or failure issues either:
a) restore access to the disks in the disk group and mount
the disk group (via ASMCMD or SQL).
or
b) Issue a force mount to the disk group to offline missing
disks and mount a normal or high redundancy disk group.
To correct the ASM_DISKSTRING in the SPFILE and propagate the
change to the GPnP profile, in sqlplus, issue the SQL command
"ALTER SYSTEM SET ASM_DISKSTRING <discovery_string> SCOPE=BOTH"

data.message: Not all endpoints are registered for listener %s

data.action: Check listener log file for that listener.

data.message: Check of storage failed: details at \\"%s\\" in \\"%s\\"

data.action: Check the Oracle Clusterware alert log and the referenced Oracle Clusterware\ntrace file for additional information.

Determine which operating system processes are accessing the mount point using an
operating system command such as 'fuser' or 'lsof' for UNIX-based platforms or 'handle'
for Windows. Close, shut down, or terminate applications and processes
accessing the mount point, then retry.

operating system command such as 'fuser' or 'lsof' for UNIX-based platforms or 'handle'
for Windows. Close, shut down, or terminate applications and processes
accessing the mount point, then retry.

data.message: unable to obtain local host name for reboot advisory log file scan
data.cause: An attempt to retrieve the local host name failed.  The scan\nfor reboot advisory files will not use host name criteria and so\nmay report occurrences for other nodes as well as this one.
data.action: Report this error to Oracle Support Services.

data.message: NIC ID not found
data.cause: Given NIC ID was not found.
data.action: Provide a correct NIC ID.\n

data.message: Could not update resource '%s'.
data.cause: There was an internal error while updating the resource.
data.action: Check the CRS daemon log file.

data.message: an error occurred accessing reboot advisory log file location: %s
data.cause:
The scan for reboot advisory log files was unable to access the
indicated file system location.  The location was skipped, so
any reboot advisory files that it contains will not be reported.
This message is accompanied by CLSU- messages containing
details of the access error.
data.action: Respond based on the error described by the accompanying CLSU-\nmessages.  This may involve re-creating the directory or\nchanging its permissions.

data.message: an error occurred searching reboot advisory log file location: %s
data.cause:
The scan for reboot advisory log files was unable to read the next
file name from the indicated file system location.  No further
processing of reboot advisory files from that location occurs.
This message is accompanied by CLSU- messages containing
details of the access error.
data.action: Respond based on the error described by the accompanying CLSU-\nmessages.

data.message: reboot advisory log file: %s is unexpectedly empty
data.cause:
The scan for reboot advisory log files encountered a file that
was empty.  This might happen (rarely) if a component is
initializing its use of reboot advisory at the same time the scan
is running.  Processing of other files in the location continues.
data.action: Frequent occurrence of this message should be reported to\nOracle Support Services.

data.message: an error occurred reading reboot advisory log file: %s
data.cause:
The scan for reboot advisory log files experienced a read error
on a reboot advisory file.  No further processing is done for that
file, but the scan continues with other files.  This message
is accompanied by CLSU- messages containing details of the
read error.
data.action: Respond based on the accompanying CLSU- messages.

data.message: an error occurred closing reboot advisory log file: %s
data.cause:
The scan for reboot advisory log files experienced a close error on
a reboot advisory file.  The scan continues with other files.  This
message is accompanied by CLSU- messages containing details of
the close error.
data.action: Report this error to Oracle Support Services.

data.message: an error occurred opening reboot advisory log file: %s
data.cause:
The scan for reboot advisory log files experienced an error when it
opened a reboot advisory file.  The scan continues with other files.
This message is accompanied by CLSU- messages containing details
of the open error.
data.action: If the error indicated in the accompanying CLSU- messages is one that\ncan be corrected, do so.  Otherwise, report this error to Oracle\nSupport Services.

data.message: an error occurred closing reboot advisory log file location: %s
data.cause:
The scan for reboot advisory log files experienced an error when it
closed the indicated file system location.  Processing of other
reboot advisory locations (if any) continues normally.
This message is accompanied by CLSU- messages containing
details of the close error.
data.action: Report this error to Oracle Support Services.

data.message: %s
data.cause:
Operating system error data related to reboot advisory file
processing was returned.  The error data is packaged in a CLSU- message
that follows "CRS-08008:".  One or more of these messages
appears after a message announcing the error condition.
data.action: Look up the embedded CLSU- message for an explanation of the\noperating system error data.  If there is no CLSU- message ID present,\ncontact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: reboot advisory log file: %s contains invalid data (length %d, error code %d)
data.cause: A reboot advisory log record read from the indicated file contained\nincorrect data.
data.action: Report this error to Oracle Support Services.

data.message: invalid network reboot advisory message detected (length %d, error code %d)
data.cause: A reboot advisory record received over the network was improperly\nformed or contained incorrect data.
data.action: Report this error to Oracle Support Services.

data.message: reboot advisory message from host: %s, component: %s, with time stamp: %s
data.cause:
A reboot advisory message was detected.  During Oracle Clusterware
startup on a given host, messages recently written to disk on that host
before a reset or reboot are detected and announced.  Subsequently,
network reboot advisory messages may be announced as they occur.  These
are reported by hosts other than the one being reset or rebooted.
This message is accompanied by other messages containing details on
what led to the reset or reboot.  The time stamp in this message
begins with either 'U' (denoting UTC time) or 'L' (denoting
local time as viewed by the issuing host).  Note that a given
reset or reboot event can produce multiple occurrences of these
messages on multiple hosts in the cluster.
data.action:
Use the reboot advisory message(s) to determine why Oracle Clusterware
caused a reset or reboot of the affected host, and respond
accordingly.  Refer to the discussion of reboot advisories in the
Oracle Clusterware administration documentation for additional
guidance.

data.message: reboot advisory message from a higher Oracle Clusterware version detected
data.cause:
A reboot advisory message from a higher version installation of
Oracle Clusterware was detected.  This is an expected
occurrence with network reboot advisories when there are nodes with
a higher Oracle Clusterware version than this node (such as during
an upgrade).  It is an unexpected condition with file reboot
advisories.
data.action:
The reboot advisory message is displayed in a following CRS-08013
message in a "raw" text form.  In the case of network reboot
advisories, the explanatory message text should be readable and
useful to determine the cause of the node reboot.  If the
reboot advisory message is from a file, report this message to
Oracle Support Services.

data.message: reboot advisory message text: %s
data.cause:
An explanatory text message associated
with a reboot advisory announced in a preceding CRS-08011 or CRS-08012
message was displayed.  These text messages are always written in US English
locale.
data.action: Refer to the descriptions of messages CRS-08011 and -08012, and\nto the Oracle Clusterware documentation on reboot advisories.

data.message: reboot advisory binary data (%d bytes%s) follows:
data.cause:
Binary data associated with a reboot advisory message was displayed.
It is followed by one or more lines of CRS-08015 message containing
the binary data formatted in hexadecimal.  If an asterisk appears
inside the parentheses, an invalid data length was detected.
data.action: Refer to the description of message CRS-08011 and -08012, and\nto the Oracle Clusterware documentation on reboot advisories.

data.cause: Hexadecimal display of binary data included in a reboot advisory log\nmessage was displayed.  The first number is an offset and is\nfollowed by up to 16 bytes of data.
data.action: Refer to the description of message CRS-08011 and -08012, and\nto the Oracle Clusterware documentation on reboot advisories.

data.message: an error occurred determining the location for reboot advisory log files
data.cause:
The search for reboot advisory log files was unable to determine
the file system location used for those files.  Processing
of reboot advisory files is skipped.  This message is accompanied
by CLSU- messages containing failure details.
This is an internal error.
data.action: Report this error to Oracle Support Services.

data.message: location: %s has %d reboot advisory log files, %d were announced and %d errors occurred
data.cause: This summary message is written during Oracle Clusterware startup if\none or more reboot advisory log files was found and examined.
data.action: This message is informational, but if the error count is nonzero\nthe associated messages (earlier in the alert log) should be examined.

data.message: warning: missing cluster identity data for reboot advisory message validation
data.cause:
During Oracle Clusterware start up, an attempt to obtain the identity of
the cluster failed.  Processing continues normally, but network
reboot advisories from nodes in other clusters may be reported in
this cluster's alert log.
data.action: Report this error to Oracle Support Services.\n

HELP MESSAGES FOR OCLUMON
9200, 3, "For help from command line   : oclumon <verb> -h\nFor help in interactive mode : <verb> -h\nCurrently supported verbs are  :\nshowtrail, showobjects, dumpnodeview, manage, version, debug, analyze, quit, exit, and help\n"

data.message: For help from command line   : oclumon <verb> -h\\nFor help in interactive mode : <verb> -h\\nCurrently supported verbs are  :\\nshowobjects, dumpnodeview, manage, version, debug, quit, exit, and help\\n

\\nMANAGE verb usage\\n=================\\n  manage [[-repos {resize <time>|changesize <memsize>|reploc <new_loc> [[-maxtime <time>]|\\n         [-maxspace <memsize>]] }]|[-get <key1> <key2>..]]\\n\\n*Where\\n
\N

-repos       = Required to specify Cluster Health Monitor repository related options\\n  -get         = Fetch manage information for one or more named keys\\n  <key1> <key2>= <key> can be repsize, reppath, master, and replica\\n  resize       = Option for resizing Cluster Health Monitor repository\\n  <time>       = Size of Cluster Health Monitor repository in number of seconds\\n
must be more than %d (1 hour) and less than %d (%d days)\\n
changesize   = Option for Change Cluster Health Monitor repository space limit\\n  <memsize>    = Size of Cluster Health Monitor repository in megabytes\\n

reploc       = Option for Change Repository Location\\n  <new_loc>    = Path to new directory e.g.: /opt/db\\n  -maxtime     = Option to specify Cluster Health Monitor repository size in terms of elapsed seconds of data capture for new location\\n  -maxspace    = Option to specify space limit for new Cluster Health Monitor repository location\\n\\n

*Requirements\\n  The local system monitor service must be running to resize the Cluster Health Monitor repository.\\n  The Cluster Logger Service must be running to resize Cluster Health Monitor repository.\\n\\n*Example :\\n  manage -get MASTER REPLICA\\n  manage -repos resize 86400\\n  manage -repos changesize 6000\\n  manage -repos reploc /opt/oracrfdb\\n  manage -repos reploc /opt/oracrfdb -maxtime 86400\\n  manage -repos reploc /opt/oracrfdb -maxspace 6000\\n

\\ndebug verb usage\\n================\\ndebug [log <daemon> <module:level>][version]\\n\\n*Where\\n  log            = To change log levels\\n  <daemon>       = Daemon whose log level has to be changed\\n                   Following daemons are supported :\\n
osysmond, ologgerd, client, all\\n
osysmond, ologgerd, client, all\\n

<module:level> = Module and level pair\\n                   Supported osysmond modules:\\n                   CRFMOND, CRFM, allcomp\\n                   Supported ologgerd modules:\\n                   CRFLOGD, CRFLDREP, CRFM, allcomp\\n                   Supported client modules:\\n                   OCLUMON, CRFM, allcomp\\n
Supported oproxyd modules:\\n                   CRFPROXY, allcomp\\n
'%s' at line no %d, Action Script must be a file.

Supported log levels:\\n                   0, 1, 2, 3\\n  version        = To display versions\\n\\n*Note\\n  modules supported for 'all' daemons: allcomp\\n  All daemons support: CRFM, allcomp\\n\\n*Example:\\n  debug log osysmond CRFMOND:3\\n

\\ndumpnodeview verb usage\\n=======================\\nThe dumpnodeview command reports monitored records in the text format. The\\ncollection of metrics for a node at a given point in time (a timestamp) is\\ncalled a node view.\\n\\n* Usage\\n  dumpnodeview [[-allnodes|-n <node1> ...] [-last <duration>|\\n                -s <timestamp> -e <timestamp>][-v][-warning]]\\n\\n
*Where\\n  -n <node1> ...   = Dump node views for given nodes\\n
-allnodes        = Dump node views for all nodes\\n  -s <timestamp>   = Specify start time for range dump of node views\\n  -e <timestamp>   = Specify end time for range dump of node views\\n

Absolute timestamp should be in \\"YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS\\"\\n                     format, for example \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\"\\n  -warning         = Print node views with warnings only\\n  -last <duration> = Dump the latest node views for a specified duration\\n
Duration should be in \\"HH24:MI:SS\\" format, for example\\n                     \\"00:45:00\\"\\n
-v               = Dump verbose node views\\n\\n

*Requirements and notes\\n  To stop continuous display, use Ctrl-C on Linux or UNIX and Esc on Windows.\\n  -s and -e need to be given together for range dumps of node views.\\n  The local System Monitor Service (osysmond) should be running to get dumps.\\n
The Cluster Logger Service (ologgerd) should be running to get dumps.\\n  When -warning is used in continuous mode, the prompt waits until interrupted.\\n\\n
*Defaults :\\n  Mode      : Continuous mode\\n\\n*Example :\\n  oclumon dumpnodeview -n node1 node2 node3 -last \\"12:00:00\\"\\n\\n

\\nSHOWTRAIL verb usage\\n====================\\n  showtrail [-n <node>] [[-diskid <diskid> <discparam>]|\\n            [-nicid <nicid> <nicparam>]|[-pid <pid> <procparams>]|\\n            [-sys <systemparam>]]\\n
[-c <regions>][-s <time> -e <time>]|[-last <time1>] [-h]\\n\\n*Where\\n
-n           = show trail for given node\\n  <node>       = node name for which trail needs to be shown\\n  -s           = To specify time for the start of range queries\\n

-e           = To specify time for the end of range queries\\n  <time>       = Absolute time to be specified within quotes in\\n                 \\"YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS\\" format, like \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\"\\n

-last        = To specify time for last queries\\n  <time1>      = Time in \\"HH24:MI:SS\\" format to be given with -last option,like  \\"00:45:00\\"\\n  -diskid      = To request trail of disk parameters\\n

-pid         = To request trail of process parameters\\n  -nicid       = To request trail of NIC parameters\\n  -sys         = To request trail of system-wide parameters\\n  <diskid>     = Disk name whose parameter's trail is required\\n

<nicid>      = NIC ID whose parameters's trail is required\\n  <pid>        = Process id whose parameter's trail is required\\n  <discparams> = Disk parameter whose trail is required\\n                 Following disk parameters are available:\\n                 qlen, totalwaittime\\n
<nicparams>  = NIC parameter whose trail is required\\n                 Following NIC parameters are available:\\n                 effectivebw , errors\\n
<procparams> = Process parameters whose trail is required\\n                 Following process parameters are available:\\n                 cputimepc, memusage, shmem, ioops,thcount, and fdcount\\n

<sysparams>  = System  parameters whose trail is required\\n                 Following system parameters are available:\\n                 usagepc, cpuqlen, cpunumprocess, openfds, numrt,\\n                 numofiosps, memfree,  numofthreads, and iowaitpc\\n

-c           = To request particular regions of interest\\n  <regions>    = List of regions of interest\\n                 Following regions are available\\n                 red,green,yellow,and orange\\n\\n

*Requirements\\n  -s and -e need to be specified together for range queries\\n  The local System Monitor Service should be running to get trail.\\n  The Cluster Logger Service should be running to get trail.\\n\\n*Defaults :\\n  Region    : ALL\\n  Time      : Last 30 min\\n\\n
*Example :\\n  showtrail -n stadn59 -diskid hda1 qlen totalwaittime -s \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\" -e \\"2007-11-12 23:15:00 \\" -c \\"red\\" \\"yellow\\"\\n
\\nshowgaps verb usage\\n====================\\n  showgaps -n <node> [[-s <time> -e <time>]|  [-last <time1>]]\\n           [-t <gapsize>] [-h]\\n\\n*Where\\n
\N

-n        = showgaps for given node\\n  <node>    = node name for which gaps need to be shown\\n  -s        = To specify time for the start of range queries\\n  -e        = To specify time for the end of range queries\\n

<time>    = Absolute time to be specified within quotes in\\n              \\"YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS\\" format, like \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\"\\n  -last     = To specify time for last queries\\n  <time1>   = Time in \\"HH24:MI:SS\\" format to be given with -last option,like \\"00:45:00\\"\\n
-t        = To specify minimum threshold for a gap\\n  <gapsize> = Gap size in seconds \\n\\n

*Requirements\\n  -s and -e need to be specified together for range queries\\n  The local System Monitor Service should be running to get gaps.\\n  The Cluster Logger Service should be running to get gaps.\\n\\n*Defaults :\\n  Threshold: 3 (least size of gap)\\n  Time: Last 30 min\\n\\n
\\nshowobjects verb usage\\n======================\\nshowobjects [[-allnodes]|[-n <node> [[-disk]|[-proc]|[-nic]]]][-time <time> [-b <band>]]\\n\\n*Where\\n
\N

-n           = Show objects for given node\\n  <node>       = Node name for which objects need to be shown\\n  -time        = Time at which objects are required\\n  <time>       = Absolute time to be specified within quotes in\\n                 \\"YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS\\" format, like \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\"\\n  -disk

= To request list of disks\\n  -nic         = To request list of network interface cards\\n  -proc        = To request list of processes\\n  -allnodes    = Shows all the nodes which can be queried\\n  -b           = For specifying maximum look up around <time> in seconds\\n  <band>       = Size of band in seconds\\n\\n
value: '%s' of the keyword: OWN_OPERATIONS is not absolute path at line no %d

*Requirements\\n  Local System Monitor Service should be running to get objects.\\n  Master loggerd should be running to get objects.\\n\\n*Defaults :\\n  Time    : Current\\n  Option  : -allnodes\\n\\n*Example :\\n  showobjects -n stadn59 -disk -time \\"2008-02-20 02:01:48\\"\\n

data.message: The Cluster Health Monitor repository location %s is inaccessible. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: An error occurred while accessing the Cluster Health repository.
data.action:
Check that the Cluster Health Monitor repository location in question has the
correct permissions. Determine whether this behavior is limited
to one node or whether it occurs across all of the nodes in
the cluster. Use the 'oclumon manage -repos reploc <location>'
command to replace the Cluster Health Monitor repository location.

data.message: The system monitor service on this host is unable to communicate with the Cluster Logger Service on host %s, and will log data to the local repository.
data.cause: Communication was lost with the Cluster Logger Service node.
data.action:
Verify all network connections between cluster nodes and repair
any problematic connections. If no network problems are found,
1. Run diagcollection.pl.
2. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The Cluster Health Monitor repository retention time cannot be changed due to lack of disk space on node %s.
data.cause: The Cluster Health Monitor retention time condition could not be\nfulfilled because the Cluster Health Monitor repository ran out\nof disk space at run time at the repository location.
data.action:
Use the 'oclumon manage -repos reploc <location>' command to replace
the Cluster Health Monitor repository with a disk location that has at least
1GB of available space per cluster node.

data.message: The OCR location %s is inaccessible. Details in %s.
data.cause: An error occurred while accessing the OCR.
data.action:
Use the ocrcheck command to validate the accessibility of the
device and its block integrity. Check that the OCR location in
question has the correct permissions. Determine whether this
behavior is limited to one node or whether it occurs across all of
the nodes in the cluster.
Use the ocrconfig command with the -replace option to replace
the OCR location.

data.action: None.

data.message: Node %s is not responding to OCR requests. Details in %s.
data.cause: Error in communicating to the OCR server on a peer node. This OCR\ndid not receive a notification regarding its peer's death within\nthe specified time.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The OCR configuration is invalid. Details in %s.
data.cause: The OCR configuration on this node does not match the OCR\nconfiguration on the other nodes in the cluster.
data.action:
Determine the OCR configuration on the other nodes in the cluster
on which Oracle Clusterware is running by using the ocrcheck
command. Run the ocrconfig command with the -repair option to
correct the OCR configuration on this node.

data.message: The OCR mirror location %s was removed.
data.cause: The OCR location was successfully removed as requested by the user.
data.action: None.

data.message: OCR cannot determine that the OCR content contains the latest updates. Details in %s.
data.cause: The OCR could not be started. The OCR location configured on this\nnode does not have the necessary votes and might not have the\nlatest updates.
data.action:
Ensure that the other nodes in the cluster have the same OCR
location configured. If the configuration on the other nodes in
the cluster does not match, then run the ocrconfig command with
the -repair option to correct the configuration on this node.
If the configurations on all of the nodes match, use the ocrdump
command to ensure that the existing OCR location has the latest
updates. Run the ocrconfig command with the -overwrite option to
correct the problem. If the se procedures do not correct the
problem, then contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The OCR service started on node %s.
data.cause: The OCR was successfully started.
data.action: None.

data.message: The OCR location in an ASM disk group is inaccessible. Details in %s.
data.cause: An error occurred while accessing the OCR file in an ASM disk group.
data.action:
Use the 'asmcmd' command to verify if the ASM instance is active.
If the ASM instance aborted, it will be restarted automatically.
Use 'ocrcheck -config' to discover the OCR locations configured,
and verify using 'asmcmd' that the disk group in question is
mounted. Mount the disk group if it is not mounted. Validate if
the behavior is limited to one node or whether it occurs across
all of the nodes in the cluster. If nothing works, use the
'ocrconfig' command with the '-replace' or '-delete' option
to replace or remove the OCR location.

data.message: Failed to import Oracle Cluster Registry from file %s
data.cause: Unable to read data from the import file and import to the\ncluster registry
data.action: Check availability of the cluster registry and the details of the\nfailure from the log file

data.message: A request to terminate the Cluster Ready Service on node %s completed successfully. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The Cluster Ready Service on the above listed node did not respond to an earlier\nrequest within the specified time. The Cluster Ready Service will be terminated to\nprevent any possible cluster hangs.
data.action:
Check the Oracle Clusterware alert log on the listed node for any problems. Check
for any reason that might not allow the Cluster Ready Service to run optimally
on the listed node. Verify network accessibility to the listed node from other nodes
in the cluster. If the problem persists, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The Cluster Ready Service on this node terminated because it detected a failure while upgrading the Oracle Cluster Registry format. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The Cluster Ready Service on the node coordinating the upgrade of\nthe Oracle Cluster Registry format terminated.
data.action:
The Oracle Cluster Registry format upgrade will be completed
by another node in the cluster. The Cluster Ready Service on the
node listed above will be automatically restarted, and will be
able to function as soon as the upgrade completes. If the problem
persists, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The Cluster Ready Service on this node terminated because it was unable to open the import file while upgrading the Oracle Cluster Registry format. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: There was a failure accessing the import file on this node. The\nCluster Ready Service on this node may not have been active during\nthe Oracle Cluster Registry format upgrade.
data.action:
The Oracle Cluster Registry format upgrade will be completed
by another node in the cluster. The Cluster Ready Service on this
node will be automatically restarted, and will be able to function
as soon as the upgrade completes. If the problem persists, contact
Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The Cluster Ready Service on this node terminated because the OCR configuration on this node is invalid. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The OCR configuration on this node did not match with the OCR\nconfiguration on the other nodes in the cluster.
data.action: The OCR configuration on this node is automatically repaired and the\nCluster Ready Service will be automatically restarted. If the\nproblem persists, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The OCR Service exited on host %s. Details in %s
data.cause: The OCR Service exited due to an internal error.
data.action: Determine whether the service has restarted. Collect Clusterware\nalert log and the CRSD log indicated in the message and contact\nOracle Support Services.

data.message: The Oracle Cluster Registry has invalid contents. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Some of the Oracle Cluster Registry contents were invalid.
data.action:
Check the log file indicated in the message for more details. Use
the 'ocrcheck' command to detect errors, and the 'ocrdump' command
to review the registry contents. If problems exist, the registry may
need to be recovered or restored. If the problem persists, contact
Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Failed %d to determine bitmap of configured nodes.\\n
The Oracle Cluster Registry backup file in an ASM disk group is inaccessible. Details in %s.
data.cause: Oracle Cluster Registry backup location did not exists, wasn't\nmounted correctly, or did not have the required permissions.
data.action:
Ensure that the backup location exists, that it is mounted correctly
and visible to all nodes in the cluster, and that its permissions
are correct. Check the ASM entries in the alert log file for more
details.

data.message: The Oracle Clusterware was forcibly upgraded without upgrading nodes %s. Version has changed from [%u, %s] to [%u, %s]. Details in %s.
data.cause: Oracle Clusterware was forcibly upgraded when the above listed\nnodes were not upgraded.
data.action: Delete the above listed nodes using the procedure documented in\nthe Oracle Clusterware documentation. If the nodes later become\naccessible, they can be added back into the cluster.

data.message: The Cluster Ready Service on this node terminated because the ASM instance was not active on this node. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The Cluster Ready Service on the node terminated because the\nASM instance was no longer active.
data.action: The Cluster Ready Services on this node will be automatically\nrestarted. If the problem persists, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The Oracle Clusterware was upgraded to [%s] on all nodes, but the cluster operating version is still [%s]. Details in [%s].
data.cause: The cluster upgrade did not complete because the root upgrade script\nfailed on the last node, the root upgrade script was interrupted by\nthe user, or the cluster upgrade is ongoing.
data.action:
Check the Oracle Clusterware alert log on all nodes for any
problems. Rerun the root upgrade script on the last node to
completion, and ensure that the cluster operating version has
changed using the 'crsctl query crs activeversion' command. If the
problem persists, run diagcollection.pl and contact Oracle Support
Services.

data.message: The Oracle Clusterware patch has completed. The patch level has changed from [%u] to [%u]. Details in %s.
data.cause: The Oracle Clusterware was successfully patched.
data.action: None.

data.message: The Oracle Cluster Registry (OCR) location in an ASM disk group [%s] does not have sufficient space. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Unable to increase the size of OCR file in the above listed disk\ngroup as the disk group was out of space.
data.action:
Delete unused files from the disk group or add additional disks to
the disk group. Refer to Oracle Clusterware administration
documentation to know about the space requirements for OCR in ASM
disk group.

data.message: The Oracle Cluster Registry backup location %s is inaccessible from node %s. Details in %s.
data.cause: The backup location provided did not exist, was not\nmounted correctly, or did not have the required permissions.
data.action:
Ensure that the backup location exists, that it is mounted
correctly and visible to all nodes in the cluster, and that the
permissions are correct. If the backup location is an
ASM disk group, check the ASM entries in the alert log file for
more details.

data.message: The Oracle Cluster Registry backup file %s is corrupt. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The backup file created by the periodic backup of the Oracle Cluster\nRegistry (OCR) failed to pass the post-backup sanity check.\nEither the OCR was corrupted or the backup was faulty.
data.action:
If the fault was introduced during the backup generation, then it
will be corrected during the next backup generation, and no action
is required. If the subsequent backup is also faulty, then the
Oracle Cluster Registry might be corrupt. Contact Oracle
Support Services.

data.message: The Oracle Cluster Registry backup file %s could not be validated. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The indicated Oracle Cluster Registry (OCR) backup file\ncould not be validated due to validation process not starting or\nfailing to run the validation check.
data.action:
If the backup was attempted as part of an automatic periodic backup,
then no action is needed. If the backup was attempted as part of a
manual backup, then try the backup again.
If the problem persists, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Started to upgrade the Oracle Clusterware. This operation may take a few minutes.\\n
There was an error setting Oracle Clusterware to rolling patch mode.
data.cause: There was an error setting Oracle Clusterware to rolling patch mode.
data.action:
Verify using the 'crsctl check crs' command that the Cluster Ready
Services (CRS) is active, and inspect the accompanying
Clusterware-specific error messages to see if there is a
correctable problem. If so, correct the problem and retry the
'crsctl start rollingpatch' command. If the problem persists,
contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: CRSD started on node %s.
data.cause: CRSD has started, possibly due to a CRS start, or a node reboot or\na CRSD restart.
data.action: None Required. You can run the command 'crsctl check crsd' to\nvalidate the health of the CRSD.

data.message: error %d encountered when sending messages to %s
data.cause: User command cannot communicate with the target process properly.
data.action: Retry again at a later time.

data.message: Unable to complete Oracle Clusterware upgrade while nodes %s have not yet upgraded\\n
data.cause:
An attempt was made to change the Oracle Clusterware operating
version before all known nodes had been upgraded. Note that some of
the nodes listed in the message may no longer be current or recent
cluster members.
data.action:
Issue the 'olsnodes' command to list current and recent cluster
members.  Any nodes listed in the error message, but not listed by
'olsnodes' have not been active recently, and should be deleted
using the procedure documented in the Oracle Clusterware
documentation.
The currently or recently active cluster members listed by
'olsnodes' should be upgraded, or, if no longer needed, deleted:
1) Run the rootupgrade.sh script on each node to be retained.
2) Delete nodes no longer desired using the procedure
documented in the Oracle Clusterware documentation.
Once all of the nodes listed in the message have been upgraded or
deleted, run the rootupgrade.sh script on an upgraded node to
complete the upgrade.
If one or more nodes could not upgraded or deleted, forcibly
upgrade the cluster using the procedure documented in the
Oracle Clusterware documentation.

data.message: Encountered error while setting key value for key '%s' in OLR. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Encountered an error while executing a batch write in OLR.
data.action: This is an internal error. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Error while executing batch for multi writes in OLR. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Encountered an error while executing a batch write in OLR.
data.action: This is an internal error. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Error enumerating subkeys for key '%s' in OLR. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Encountered an error while reading subkey values in OLR.
data.action: This is an internal error. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Failed to retrieve the maximum value supported in OLR. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Could not read the maximum value size from registry.
data.action: This is an internal error. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Failed to add a delete key operation for key '%s' to a batch in OLR. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Encountered internal error while deleting key in OLR.
data.action: This is an internal error. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Oracle High Availability Service aborted due to an unexpected error [%s]. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Look at the associated error message to fix the underlying issue.
data.action: If the problem persists, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Node '%s' has a pending role change; Oracle High Availability Services needs to be restarted.
data.cause: A 'crsctl stop cluster' command was run after a node's role has changed.

data.message: EVMD started on node %s.
data.cause: EVMD has started either because of a CRS start, a node reboot,\nor an EVMD restart.
data.action: None required. You can run the 'crsctl check evmd' command to validate the health of EVMD.

data.message: EVMD aborted on node %s. Error [%s]. Details in %s.
data.cause: EVMD has aborted due to an internal error. Check the EVMD log file\nto determine the cause.
data.action: Determine whether the EVMD is auto-started and contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The Event Management Service terminated on node %s. Listening port %d is in use by another application. Details in %s.
data.cause: The Event Management Service has aborted because the\nconfigured listening port is being used by another\napplication on this node.

data.message: CSSD Reconfiguration complete. Active nodes are %s.
data.cause: A node joined or left the cluster.
data.action: None.

data.message: CSSD aborted on node %s. Error [%s]; details in %s.
data.cause: The CSS daemon aborted on the listed node with the listed return\ncode.
data.action: Collect the CSS daemon logs from all nodes and any CSS daemon core\nfiles and contact Oracle Support.

data.message: CSSD on node %s has been shut down.
data.cause: The CSS daemon on the listed node was terminated.
data.action: None.

data.message: CSSD voting file is offline: %s; details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The listed voting file became unusable on the local node.
data.action: Verify that the filesystem containing the listed voting file is\navailable on the local node.

data.message: CSSD voting file is online: %s; details in %s.
data.cause: The CSS daemon has detected a valid configured voting file.
data.action: None.

data.message: The number of voting files available, %d, is less than the minimum number of voting files required, %d, resulting in CSSD termination to ensure data integrity; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The number of voting files has decreased to a number of files\nthat is insufficient.
data.action: Locate previous 1604, 1613, 1614 and 1615 messages and take\naction as indicated by those messages.

data.message: Node %s is being evicted in cluster incarnation %d; details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The local node has detected that the indicated node is still\nactive, but not able to communicate with this node, so is\nforcibly removing the indicated node from the cluster.
data.action: Collect the CSS daemon logs from all nodes and any CSS daemon core\nfiles and contact Oracle Support.

data.message: This node was evicted by node %d, %s; details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The local node was evicted by the indicated node.
data.action: Collect the CSS daemon logs from all nodes and any CSS daemon core\nfiles and contact Oracle Support.

data.message: This node is unable to communicate with other nodes in the cluster and is going down to preserve cluster integrity; details at %s in %s.
data.cause:
Communication was lost with some nodes of the cluster and this
node detected that another sub-cluster was designated to be the
surviving sub-cluster. This node went down to preserve data
integrity.
data.action:
Verify all network connections between cluster nodes and
repair any problematic connections. If there do not appear
to be any network problems,
1. collect the CSS daemon logs, system messages and
any CSS daemon core files from all nodes and
2. contact Oracle Support.

data.message: CSSD on node %s detected a problem and started to shutdown.
data.cause: The CSS daemon on the listed node detected a problem and started to shutdown.
data.action: Check the CRS alert log.\n

data.message: timed out when waiting for response from %s
data.cause: the target process does not return acknowledgment in time.
data.action: Retry again at a later time.

data.message: Found no resources to stop.
Network communication with node %s (%d) missing for 90%% of timeout interval.  Removal of this node from cluster in %d.%03d seconds
data.cause: Did not receive heartbeat messages from the node. This could be\ndue to network problems or failure of the listed node.
data.action:
Check if the private interconnect network used by cluster is
functioning properly, including all the cables, network cards,
switches/routers etc. between this node and listed node. Correct
any problems discovered.

data.message: Network communication with node %s (%d) missing for 75%% of timeout interval.  Removal of this node from cluster in %d.%03d seconds
data.cause: Did not receive heartbeat messages from the node. This could be\ndue to network problems or failure of the listed node.
data.action:
Check if the private interconnect network used by cluster is
functioning properly, including all the cables, network cards,
switches/routers etc. between this node and listed node. Correct
any problems discovered.

data.message: Network communication with node %s (%d) missing for 50%% of timeout interval.  Removal of this node from cluster in %d.%03d seconds
data.cause: Did not receive heartbeat messages from the node. This could be\ndue to network problems or failure of listed node.
data.action:
Check if the private interconnect network used by cluster is
functioning properly, including all the cables, network cards,
switches/routers etc. between this node and listed node. Correct
any problems discovered.

data.message: No I/O has completed after 90%% of the maximum interval. Voting file %s will be considered not functional in %d milliseconds
data.cause: Voting device I/O has not completed for a long time. This could be due\nsome error with the device the voting file is on or in some element\nin the path of the I/O to the device.
data.action:
Verify that the device is working properly including all elements
in the I/O path. The voting file listed will be considered inactive
in the number of milliseconds specified. Failure of a majority of
devices will result in node reboot.

data.message: No I/O has completed after 75%% of the maximum interval. Voting file %s will be considered not functional in %d milliseconds
data.cause: Voting device I/O has not completed for a long time. This could be due\nsome error with the device the voting file is on or in some element\nin the path of the I/O to the device.
data.action:
Verify that the device is working properly including all elements
in the I/O path. The voting file listed will be considered inactive
in the number of milliseconds specified. Failure of a majority of
devices will result in node reboot.

data.message: No I/O has completed after 50%% of the maximum interval. Voting file %s will be considered not functional in %d milliseconds
data.cause: Voting device I/O has not completed for a long time. This could be due\nsome error with the device the voting file is on or in some element\nin the path of the I/O to the device.
data.action:
Verify that the device is working properly including all elements
in the I/O path. The voting file listed will be considered inactive
in the number of milliseconds specified. Failure of a majority of
devices will result in node reboot.

data.message: The BMC device used for IPMI at IP address %s is not properly configured for ADMIN access; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The IPMI BMC is not configured to support the ADMIN access methods\nrequired by Oracle Clusterware.
data.action:
Consult the clusterware admin manual for proper procedures in
configuring BMC. Use the BMC configuration tool (ipmitool
or ipmiutil) command to check and verify
that the current configuration supports either MD5 or password
validation for ADMIN access.

data.message: The information required to do node kill for node %s is incomplete; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Incomplete config information stored in Cluster Registry for node\nkill.
data.action: Make sure all the information pertaining to the node kill method

data.message: The requested node kill information change could not be validated by node %s; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Unable to validate the node kill information for this node.
data.action: Additional information can be found in the CRS alert log of\nthe node that performed the validation.\n

data.message: The node kill information of node %s could not be validated by this node due to failure in connecting to the IPMI device; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Unable to validate the node kill information for this node.
data.action: Additional information can be found in the CSSD logs.\n

data.message: The node kill information of node %s could not be validated by this node due to invalid authorization information; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Unable to validate the kill information for this node.
data.action: Additional information can be found in the CSSD logs.\n

data.message: The IPMI configuration data for this node stored in the Oracle registry is incomplete; details at %s in %s
data.cause: All the necessary information such as IPMI username, password and\nIP address are not present.
data.action:
Make sure all the information(BMC IPMI username, password and
IP address) are present. Use commands 'crsctl set css ipmiaddr'
and 'crsctl set css ipmiadmin' for this.

data.message: The IPMI node kill information could not be validated due to inability to connect to the IPMI device at BMC IP address provided %s; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Unable to validate the BMC IPMI IP address provided.
data.action: Additional information can be found in the CSSD logs.\n

data.message: The IPMI node kill information of BMC at IP address %s could not be validated due to invalid authorization information. The BMC username provided is '%s'; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Unable to validate the BMC IPMI UserName and password provided.
data.action: Additional information can be found in the CSSD logs.\n

data.message: The requested Node kill information change succeeds vacuously because there is no other node in cluster to validate.
data.cause: Unable to validate the credentials because this is the sole node in\nthe cluster.
data.action: To complete the valdidation, shut down the clusterware stack on\nthis node, start another node and restart the stack on this node.\n

data.message: Node %s, number %d, was shut down
A Configuration change request completed successfully
A Configuration change request failed because another configuration change is in progress; Details at %s in %s
A Configuration change request failed because read of existing voting files failed; Details at %s in %s
A Configuration change request failed because write to new voting files failed; Details at %s in %s
A configuration change request failed because not all the new voting files were discovered; Details at %s in %s
data.cause: One or more of the voting files being added were not discovered.\nMessage 1638 identifies the unique ID(s) of the file(s) that\ncould not be found.
data.action:
Verify if the discovery string is adequate to discover the new
voting files. If not, modify discovery string using command
'crsctl replace discoverystring xxxxx'.

data.message: A configuration change request failed because one or more nodes are not a sufficient Clusterware version level; Details at %s in %s
data.cause: One ore more nodes are not a sufficient version level.
data.action: Configuration change would not be successful until all nodes are at\nat the latest version. Try after all the nodes are upgraded.\n

data.message: connection by user %s to %s refused
data.cause: User command cannot connect to the target process.
data.action: The user may not have sufficient privilege to connect.

data.message: Node %s is being removed from the cluster in cluster incarnation %d
data.cause: The local node is removing the indicated node from the cluster\nbecause it appears to be dead.
data.action:
Verify that the node that was removed, or the Oracle Clusterware
on that node, was down.  The CRS alert log of the node that was
removed has information regarding why the node, or clusterware
on the node, was no longer active.  If the node was still up
and Oracle Clusterware still active on that node, collect the
CSS daemon logs from all nodes and any CSS daemon core files
and contact Oracle Support.

data.message: CSSD failed to register group %s in vendor clusterware; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The local node is not able to register the group of\nvendor clusterware.
data.action: Verify that the vendor clusterware is installed and configured correctly.\n

data.message: CSSD is unable to determine cluster name; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Name of the cluster cannot be determined from configuration.
data.action: Verify that Oracle Clusterware installation was successful.\n

data.message: CSSSD failed to initialize vendor clusterware; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The local node is not able to attach vendor clusterware.
data.action: Verify that the vendor clusterware is installed and configured correctly.\n

data.message: The CSS daemon was started in exclusive mode but found an active CSS daemon on node %s and is terminating; details at %s in %s
data.cause:
The CSS daemon was started in exclusive mode, which requires
that the clusterware stack is down on all other nodes to ensure
data integrity.  A CSS daemon was detected on another node,
so the CSS daemon on this node is terminating.
data.action: Stop the Oracle clusterware stack that is running on the\nindicated node.\n

data.message: Unable to locate configured voting file with ID %s; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The voting file with unique the ID indicated in the message\nwas not found during the voting file discovery phase of CSS\ninitialization.
data.action:
Verify that all configured voting files are accessible on this
node.  Any voting files that are not accessible should be
removed and replaced with accessible voting files using the
appropriate 'crsctl' commands.

data.message: Unable to locate voting file with ID %s that is being added to the list of configured voting files; details at %s in %s
data.cause:
The voting file with the unique ID indicated in the message
was not found during the voting file discovery phase of CSS
initialization.  This voting file is in the process of being
added to the list of configured voting files.
data.action:
Verify that all voting files to be added are accessible on this
node.  Any voting files that are not accessible should be
removed and replaced with accessible voting files using the
appropriate 'crsctl' commands.

data.message: Rejecting configuration change %u:%u because another configuration change is already in progress; details at %s in %s
data.cause: A configuration change was requested, but another configuration\nchange is already in progress and only one configuration change\nmay be processed at a time.
data.action: Wait for the current configuration change to complete, then\nresubmit this configuration change.\n

data.message: Rejecting configuration change %u:%u because one or more new voting files in the new configuration could not be found; details at %s in %s
data.cause: A configuration change that involved the addition of voting\nfiles is being rejected because some of the new voting files\nwere not located.
data.action:
Verify that the voting file name is correct and that it is
accessible on this node, if the voting files are not managed
by ASM.  Message number 1638 provides greater detail.

data.message: Rejecting configuration change %u:%u because only %u of the required %u voting files of the new configuration were located; details at %s in %s
data.cause:
A configuration change that involved a change to the list of
voting files is being rejected because a sufficient number
of voting files in the new configuration could not be
located.
data.action: Verify that all voting files in the new configuration\nare accessible on this node.\n

data.message: Node %d is using a different CSS configuration from the one used by this node; this node is terminating to preserve integrity; details at %s in %s
data.cause:
Another node in the cluster is using a different set of
CSS configuration values, such as misscount or voting files.
Inconsistency can result in data corruption, so this node is
terminating to avoid data corruption.
data.action:
Collect Clusterware alert log and the CSSD log indicated in
the message as well as the CSS daemon logs of all other nodes
in the cluster and contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Failed to format the CSS voting disk %s
data.cause: Problems were encountered attempting to access the voting file.
data.action: Verify that the voting file can be accessed, the file exists,\nhas the proper ownership and permissions, etc.\n

data.message: The initialization of the EXADATA fencing facility failed in start with error ORA-%d; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The start of the initialization of the EXADATA fencing facility\nfailed with the error code shown.
data.action: See the Action section of the error message shown.\n

data.message: The initialization of the EXADATA fencing facility failed in completion with error ORA-%d; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The completion of the initialization of the EXADATA fencing\nfacility failed with the error code shown.
data.action: See the Action section of the error message shown.\n

data.message: Creation of a EXADATA fence identifier failed with error ORA-%d; details at %s in %s
data.cause: An attempt to create an identifier for a fence to an EXADATA\ndevice failed with the error code shown.
data.action: See the Action section of the error message shown.\n

data.message: Initialization of a EXADATA fence failed with error ORA-%d; details at %s in %s
data.cause: An attempt to initiate a fence to an EXADATA device failed with\nthe error code shown.
data.action: See the Action section of the error message shown.\n

data.message: Completion of queued EXADATA fence requests failed with error ORA-%d; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Previously queued fence requests to an EXADATA device failed with\nthe error code shown.
data.action: See the Action section of the error message shown.\n

data.message: An I/O error occurred for voting file: %s; details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The listed voting file became inaccessible.
data.action: Verify that the filesystem containing the listed voting file is\navailable on the local node.\n

data.message: Configuration change %u:%u rejected by node %u %s; details at %s in %s
data.cause: A new configuration change request from this node was not\naccepted due to another node rejecting the change.
data.action: Check the CRS alert log of the node rejecting this configuration\nchange for more details.\n

data.message: Configuration change %u:%u rejected because it would make the active version of node %u lower than the current setting %s of this node; details at %s in %s
data.cause: A new configuration change request from another node was not\naccepted because the new Active Version in the request is lower\nthan this node's Active Version.
data.action: Ensure that the new Active Version is not lower than the current\nActive Version of the nodes in the cluster.\n

data.message: Starting clean up of CRSD resources.
