oclumon was not able to connect to the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository because no listener was available.
data.cause: An attempt to connect to the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository failed because no Grid Infrastructure Management Repository listener was running.
data.action: Use the 'srvctl status mgmtlsnr' command to confirm that Grid Infrastructure Management Repository listener is running. If it is not, start it using the 'srvctl start mgmtlsnr' command. If the problem persists, run 'diagcollection.pl' and contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: oclumon was not able to retrieve the security keys from the wallet.
data.cause: An attempt to retrieve the security keys from the wallet failed.
data.action: Run the 'crsctl query wallet -type MGMTDB' command to verify that the wallet exists. If the problem persists, contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: oclumon was not able to connect to the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository because a Cluster Synchronization Services request failed.
data.cause: An attempt to connect to the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository failed due to a Cluster Synchronization Services failure.
data.action: If the problem persists, run 'diagcollection.pl' and contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: Cluster Health Monitor repository retention change failed. Aborting retention change. Error: %s
data.cause: An error occurred while setting the Cluster Health Monitor repository size on the cluster logger service.
data.action:
Take the following steps.
1) Examine the accompanying ORA-nnnnn or CRS-nnnn error messages. If possible, correct the issue reported.
2) Issue a 'srvctl status mgmtdb' command to determine the status of the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository database. If it is not online, examine the database instance alert log to determine what happened.
3) If you are unable to determine or correct the problem, run 'diagcollection.pl' and contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Error %s: %s is an invalid node name.
data.cause: The 'oclumon' command could not be carried out as entered because the node name cited in the message was invalid. The cited node name was ignored and the query executed with any remaining names.
data.action:
Reissue the 'oclumon' command, if desired, supplying a valid name for the node name cited in the message. Refer to the product documentation or to command online help for information.

HELP MESSAGES FOR OCLUMON
9200, 3, "For help from command line   : oclumon <verb> -h\nFor help in interactive mode : <verb> -h\nCurrently supported verbs are  :\nshowtrail, showobjects, dumpnodeview, manage, version, debug, analyze, quit, exit, and help\n"

data.message: For help from command line   : oclumon <verb> -h\\nFor help in interactive mode : <verb> -h\\nCurrently supported verbs are  :\\nshowobjects, dumpnodeview, manage, version, debug, analyze, quit, exit, and help\\n
For help from command line   : oclumon <verb> -h\\nFor help in interactive mode : <verb> -h\\nCurrently supported verbs are  :\\ndumpnodeview, manage, version, debug, analyze, quit, exit, and help\\n

\\nmanage verb usage\\n=================\\n  manage [[-repos {resize <time>|changesize <memsize>|reploc <new_loc> [[-maxtime <time>]|\\n         [-maxspace <memsize>]] }]|[-get <key1> <key2>..]\\n[-enable diagsnap] |[-disable diagsnap]]\\n\\n*Where\\n
\N

-repos       = Required to specify Cluster Health Monitor repository related options\\n  -get         = Fetch manage information for one or more named keys\\n  <key1> <key2>= <key> can be repsize, reppath, master and replica\\n  resize       = Option for resizing Cluster Health Monitor repository\\n  <time>       = Size of Cluster Health Monitor repository in number of seconds\\n
must be more than %d (1 hour) and less than %d (%d days)\\n
changesize   = Option for Change Cluster Health Monitor repository space limit\\n  <memsize>    = Size of Cluster Health Monitor repository in megabytes\\n

reploc       = Option for Change Repository Location\\n  <new_loc>    = Path to new directory e.g.: /opt/db\\n  -maxtime     = Option to specify Cluster Health Monitor repository size in terms of elapsed seconds of data capture for new location\\n  -maxspace    = Option to specify space limit for new Cluster Health Monitor repository location\\n -enable diagsnap     = Option to enable diagsnap  -disable diagsnap     = Option to disable diagsnap\\n\\\\n

*Requirements\\n  The local system monitor service must be running to resize the Cluster Health Monitor repository.\\n  The Cluster Logger Service must be running to resize Cluster Health Monitor repository.\\n\\n*Example :\\n  manage -get MASTER REPLICA\\n  manage -repos resize 86400\\n  manage -repos changesize 6000\\n  manage -repos reploc /opt/oracrfdb\\n  manage -repos reploc /opt/oracrfdb -maxtime 86400\\n  manage -repos reploc /opt/oracrfdb -maxspace 6000\\n

\\ndebug verb usage\\n================\\ndebug {log <daemon> <module:level> | version}\\n\\n*Where\\n  log            = To change log levels\\n  <daemon>       = Daemon whose log level has to be changed\\n                   Following daemons are supported :\\n
osysmond, ologgerd, client, all\\n
osysmond, ologgerd, client, all\\n

<module:level> = Module and level pair\\n                   Supported osysmond modules:\\n                   CRFMOND, CRFM, allcomp\\n                   Supported ologgerd modules:\\n                   CRFLOGD, CRFLDREP, CRFM, allcomp\\n                   Supported client modules:\\n                   OCLUMON, CRFM, allcomp\\n
Supported oproxyd modules:\\n                   CRFPROXY, allcomp\\n

Supported log levels:\\n                   0, 1, 2, 3\\n  version        = To display versions\\n\\n*Note\\n  modules supported for 'all' daemons: allcomp\\n  All daemons support: CRFM, allcomp\\n\\n*Example:\\n  debug log osysmond CRFMOND:3\\n

\\ndumpnodeview verb usage\\n=======================\\nThe dumpnodeview command reports monitored records in the text format. The\\ncollection of metrics for a node at a given point in time (a timestamp) is\\ncalled a node view.\\n\\n* Usage\\n

dumpnodeview [-allnodes | -n <node1> ...] [-last <duration> |\\n                -s <timestamp> -e <timestamp>][-i <interval>][-v]\\n                [-system][-process][-device][filesystem][-nic]\\n                [-protoerr][-cpu][-topconsumer][-format <format type>]\\n                [-dir <directory> [-append]]\\n\\n

*Where\\n  -n <node1> ...   = Dump node views for specified nodes\\n  -allnodes        = Dump node views for all nodes\\n  -s <timestamp>   = Specify start time for range dump of node views\\n  -e <timestamp>   = Specify end time for range dump of node views\\n

Absolute timestamp must be in \\"YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS\\"\\n                     format, for example \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\"\\n  -last <duration> = Dump the latest node views for a specified duration.\\n
Duration must be in \\"HH24:MI:SS\\" format, for example\\n                     \\"00:45:00\\"\\n
-i               = Dump node views separated by the specified\\n                     interval in seconds. Must be a multiple of 5.\\n

-v               = Dump verbose node views containing all parts.\\n  -system, -cpu,.. = Dump each indicate node view parts.\\n  -format <format type> = format of the output.\\n                     <format type> can be legacy, tabular, or csv.\\n                     The default format is tabular.\\n  -dir <directory> = Dump node view part to file(s) in spceified dir.\\n                     With -append, will append the files. Overwrite otherwise.\\n\\n

*Requirements and notes\\n  To stop continuous display, use Ctrl-C on Linux or UNIX and Esc on Windows.\\n  -s and -e need to be specified together for range dumps of node views.\\n  The local System Monitor Service (osysmond) must be running to get dumps.\\n
The Cluster Logger Service (ologgerd) must be running to get dumps.\\n  For screen reader user, please use option -format legacy.\\n\\n

*Defaults :\\n  Mode      : Continuous mode\\n\\n*Example :\\n  oclumon dumpnodeview -n node1 node2 node3 -last \\"12:00:00\\"\\n  oclumon dumpnodeview -last \\"00:10:00\\" -i 30\\n  oclumon dumpnodeview -format csv -system -cpu -topconsumer\\n

\\nSHOWTRAIL verb usage\\n====================\\n  showtrail [-n <node>] [[-diskid <diskid> <discparam>]|\\n            [-nicid <nicid> <nicparam>]|[-pid <pid> <procparams>]|\\n            [-sys <systemparam>]]\\n
[-c <regions>][-s <time> -e <time>]|[-last <time1>] [-h]\\n\\n*Where\\n
-n           = show trail for specified node\\n  <node>       = node name for which trail needs to be shown\\n  -s           = To specify time for the start of range queries\\n

-e           = To specify time for the end of range queries\\n  <time>       = Absolute time to be specified within quotes in\\n                 \\"YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS\\" format, like \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\"\\n

-last        = To specify time for last queries\\n  <time1>      = Time in \\"HH24:MI:SS\\" format to be specified with -last option,like  \\"00:45:00\\"\\n  -diskid      = To request trail of disk parameters\\n

-pid         = To request trail of process parameters\\n  -nicid       = To request trail of NIC parameters\\n  -sys         = To request trail of system-wide parameters\\n  <diskid>     = Disk name whose parameter's trail is required\\n

<nicid>      = NIC ID whose parameters's trail is required\\n  <pid>        = Process id whose parameter's trail is required\\n  <discparams> = Disk parameter whose trail is required\\n                 Following disk parameters are available:\\n                 qlen, totalwaittime\\n
<nicparams>  = NIC parameter whose trail is required\\n                 Following NIC parameters are available:\\n                 effectivebw , errors\\n
<procparams> = Process parameters whose trail is required\\n                 Following process parameters are available:\\n                 cputimepc, memusage, shmem, ioops,thcount, and fdcount\\n

<sysparams>  = System  parameters whose trail is required\\n                 Following system parameters are available:\\n                 usagepc, cpuqlen, cpunumprocess, openfds, numrt,\\n                 numofiosps, memfree,  numofthreads, and iowaitpc\\n

-c           = To request particular regions of interest\\n  <regions>    = List of regions of interest\\n                 Following regions are available\\n                 red,green,yellow,and orange\\n\\n

*Requirements\\n  -s and -e need to be specified together for range queries\\n  The local System Monitor Service should be running to get trail.\\n  The Cluster Logger Service should be running to get trail.\\n\\n*Defaults :\\n  Region    : ALL\\n  Time      : Last 30 min\\n\\n
*Example :\\n  showtrail -n stadn59 -diskid hda1 qlen totalwaittime -s \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\" -e \\"2007-11-12 23:15:00 \\" -c \\"red\\" \\"yellow\\"\\n
\\nshowgaps verb usage\\n====================\\n  showgaps -n <node> [[-s <time> -e <time>]|  [-last <time1>]]\\n           [-t <gapsize>] [-h]\\n\\n*Where\\n
\N

-n        = showgaps for specified node\\n  <node>    = node name for which gaps need to be shown\\n  -s        = To specify time for the start of range queries\\n  -e        = To specify time for the end of range queries\\n

<time>    = Absolute time to be specified within quotes in\\n              \\"YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS\\" format, like \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\"\\n  -last     = To specify time for last queries\\n  <time1>   = Time in \\"HH24:MI:SS\\" format to be specified with -last option,like \\"00:45:00\\"\\n
-t        = To specify minimum threshold for a gap\\n  <gapsize> = Gap size in seconds \\n\\n

*Requirements\\n  -s and -e need to be specified together for range queries\\n  The local System Monitor Service should be running to get gaps.\\n  The Cluster Logger Service should be running to get gaps.\\n\\n*Defaults :\\n  Threshold: 3 (least size of gap)\\n  Time: Last 30 min\\n\\n
\\nshowobjects verb usage\\n======================\\nshowobjects [[-allnodes]|[-n <node> [[-disk]|[-proc]|[-nic]]]][-time <time> [-b <band>]]\\n\\n*Where\\n
\N

-n           = Show objects for specified node\\n  <node>       = Node name for which objects need to be shown\\n  -time        = Time at which objects are required\\n  <time>       = Absolute time to be specified within quotes in\\n                 \\"YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS\\" format, like \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\"\\n  -disk

= To request list of disks\\n  -nic         = To request list of network interface cards\\n  -proc        = To request list of processes\\n  -allnodes    = Shows all the nodes which can be queried\\n  -b           = For specifying maximum look up around <time> in seconds\\n  <band>       = Size of band in seconds\\n\\n

*Requirements\\n  Local System Monitor Service should be running to get objects.\\n  Master loggerd should be running to get objects.\\n\\n*Defaults :\\n  Time    : Current\\n  Option  : -allnodes\\n\\n*Example :\\n  showobjects -n stadn59 -disk -time \\"2008-02-20 02:01:48\\"\\n
\\nanalyze verb usage\\n=======================\\nThe analyze command reports problems pertaining to Oracle Clusterware, ASM and Database.\\n\\n
*Usage\\nanalyze [-allnodes|-n <node1> ...] [-s <time> -e <time>|-last <duration>]\\n        [-r <severity>] [-y <component> ...] [-x <instance name>] [-v]\\n\\n
*Where\\n  -n <node1> ...     = To limit the display to problems associated with the specified nodes\\n
-allnodes          = To analyze problems for all nodes\\n  -s                 = To specify time for the start of range queries\\n  -e                 = To specify time for the end of range queries\\n
Voting File Wait Time
-r                 = To limit the display to a subset of problems based on severity\\n                       The severity can be HIGH, MEDIUM or LOW\\n
-b                 = To specify a directory containing user models, and override the default models\\n
-d                 = To specify a directory containing data for analysis\\n                       If a component is specified, it must be ASM, DATABASE or both\\n
-y <component> ... = To limit the display to a subset of problems based on component\\n                       The component can be CLUSTERWARE or DATABASE\\n
-x                 = To limit the display to problems associated with a specific database instance\\n                       The component specified must be DATABASE\\n
-v                 = To display results in a verbose format\\n
\\n\\n*Requirements and notes\\n  To stop the display, use Ctrl-C on Linux and Esc on Windows\\n  The -s and -e options need to be specified together for range queries\\n
Analysis for the last 30 minutes is displayed when no time or duration is specified  \\n  The Grid Infrastructure Management Repository must be active to complete the analysis\\n\\n

*Example:\\n  oclumon analyze -n stadn59 -s \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\" -e \\"2007-11-12 23:35:00\\" -y CLUSTERWARE\\n  oclumon analyze -n stadn19 -s \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\" -e \\"2007-11-12 23:35:00\\" -y DATABASE -x storedb3\\n  oclumon analyze -allnodes -s \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\" -e \\"2007-11-12 23:35:00\\" -y CLUSTERWARE\\n
\\ncalibrate verb usage\\n=======================\\nThe calibrate command calibrates the models pertaining to Oracle Clusterware, ASM and Database.\\n\\n

*Usage\\ncalibrate {-s <time> -e <time>}\\n          -y <component>\\n          {-allnodes|-n <host>|-o <serverpool name>|{-w <database name> [-o <serverpool name>]}}\\n          [-q <model name>] [-v]\\n\\n
*Where\\n  -s                 = To specify the start time of the data used for model calibration\\n  -e                 = To specify the end time of the data used for model calibration\\n
<time>             = Absolute time to be specified within quotes in\\n                       \\"YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS\\" format, like \\"2012-11-12 23:05:00\\"\\n
-y <component>     = To calibrate a specific model based on the component\\n                       The component can be CLUSTERWARE, ASM or DATABASE.\\n
-allnodes          = Calibrate models for all nodes\\n                       The component specified must be CLUSTERWARE.\\n
-n <host>          = To limit the model calibration to a specific host\\n                       The component specified must be CLUSTERWARE.\\n
-w <database name> = To limit the model calibration to a specific database\\n                       The component specified must be DATABASE.\\n
-o <serverpool name> = To limit the model calibration to a specific server pool in a policy-managed cluster\\n
-v                 = To display results in a verbose format\\n

-q <model name>    = Optional model provided by user.\\n                       If a model is not provided, the current model is calibrated.\\n                       If a model is provided, then an existing model is calibrated if one exists.\\n                       If a model is provided, and it does not exist, then an existing model is cloned, and the cloned model is calibrated.\\n
\\n*Requirements and notes\\n  To stop the display, use Ctrl-C on Linux and Esc on Windows.\\n  The -s and -e options need to be specified together for range queries.\\n
The Grid Infrastructure Management Repository must be active to complete the calibration.\\n
An instance of the database must be active on the node the command is issued when the DATABASE component is specified.
The instance whose model will be calibrated may be remote and does not have to be active.\\n
The target i.e. database or host will not be monitored while the model is being calibrated.\\n
The command must be issued by a privileged user.\\n\\n
*Example :\\n  oclumon calibrate -s \\"2012-11-12 09:05:00\\" -e \\"2012-11-12 11:05:00\\" -y CLUSTERWARE -n stadn59\\n

oclumon calibrate -s \\"2012-11-12 10:05:00\\" -e \\"2012-11-12 12:35:00\\" -y DATABASE -w storedb\\n  oclumon calibrate -s \\"2012-11-12 22:05:00\\" -e \\"2012-11-12 23:35:00\\" -y DATABASE -w storedb -o SERVERPOOLBIG -q BACKUP\\n

\\nManage verb usage\\n=================\\n  manage -repos {checkretentiontime <time> | changerepossize <memsize>} |\\n\\t -get {<key1> [<key2> ...] | alllogger [-details] | mylogger [-details]} |\\n\\t -enable {diagsnap} | -disable {diagsnap} \\n\\n*Where\\n
\N

-repos\\t\\t= Required to specify Cluster Health Monitor repository related options\\n  -get\\t\\t\\t= Fetch manage information for one or more named keys\\n  <key1> <key2>\\t\\t= <key> can be repsize, reppath, master, mylogger and alllogger \\n  alllogger\\t\\t= Special key with -get to get list of all nodes running Cluster Logger Service

\\n  mylogger\\t\\t= Special key with -get to get the node running the Cluster Logger Service which is serving the current node\\n  -details\\t\\t= Option with alllogger and mylogger for listing nodes served by the Cluster Logger Service\\n  checkretentiontime    = Option to confirm whether specified time retention can be realized for current Cluster Health Monitor repository size\\n  <time>\\t\\t= Retention of Cluster Health Monitor repository in number of seconds\\n
changerepossize\\t= Option for Change Cluster Health Monitor repository space limit\\n  <memsize>\\t\\t= Size of Cluster Health Monitor repository in megabytes\\n\\n

-csvlog\\t\\t= Options related to comma separated value output from Cluster Health Monitor\\n  status\\t\\t= Comma separated values feature status: ON or OFF.  Feature is ON by default.\\n  interval <time>\\t= Option to specify comma separated values sampling interval in whole clock seconds. Default sampling interval is 60 seconds.\\n
logduration <size>\\t= Option to specify comma separated values data file boundary in megabytes. Default file boundary is 10 megabytes.\\n\\n

*Requirements\\n  The local cluster synchronization service must be running to change the retention time of the Cluster Health Monitor repository.\\n  The Cluster Logger Service must be running to change the retention time of the Cluster Health Monitor repository.\\n\\n*Example :\\n
Voting file '%s' has an average wait time of %d milliseconds.
manage -get MASTER \\n  manage -repos checkretentiontime 86400\\n  manage -repos changerepossize 6000\\n  manage -get alllogger -details\\n\\n
manage -csvlog status off\\n  manage -csvlog interval 50\\n  manage -csvlog logduration 300\\n
-enable diagsnap\\t= Option to enable diagsnap script\\n  -disable diagsnap\\t= Option to disable diagsnap script\\n

data.message: The Cluster Health Monitor repository location %s is inaccessible. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: An error occurred while accessing the Cluster Health repository.
data.action:
Check that the Cluster Health Monitor repository location in question has the
correct permissions. Determine whether this behavior is limited
to one node or whether it occurs across all of the nodes in
the cluster. Use the 'oclumon manage -repos reploc <location>'
command to replace the Cluster Health Monitor repository location.

data.message: The System Monitor Service on this host is unable to communicate with the Cluster Logger Service on host %s, and will log the Cluster Health Monitor data to the local repository.
data.cause: Communication was lost with the Cluster Logger Service node.
data.action:
Verify all network connections between cluster nodes and repair
any problematic connections. If network problems are not found,
execute the following steps:
1. Run diagcollection.pl.
2. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The Cluster Health Monitor repository retention time cannot be changed due to lack of disk space on node %s.
data.cause: The Cluster Health Monitor retention time condition could not be\nfulfilled because the Cluster Health Monitor repository ran out\nof disk space at run time at the repository location.
data.action:

the Cluster Health Monitor repository with a disk location that has at least
1GB of available space per cluster node.

data.action: Use the 'srvctl status mgmtlsnr' command to confirm that Grid Infrastructure Management Repository listener is running. If it is not, start it using the 'srvctl start mgmtlsnr' command. If the problem persists, run 'diagcollection.pl' and contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: The storage of Grid Infrastructure Management Repository is %u%% full. The storage location is '%s'.
data.cause: The storage of Grid Infrastructure Management Repository was close to full. This storage can be a shared file system or an Oracle ASM disk group.
data.action: Make sure there is sufficient free space in repository location.\n

data.message: Grid Infrastructure Management Repository was not available on the node %s. The System Monitor Service will store the data in its local repository on all nodes. \\n%s
data.cause: Grid Infrastructure Management Repository was initializing or was shutting down when the Cluster Logger Service tried to connect, insert or delete the data.
data.action: Check if the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository is online using the 'srvctl status mgmtdb' command. If it is offline, start it using the 'srvctl start mgmtdb' command.\n

data.message: The Cluster Logger Service was not able to retrieve the security keys from the wallet.
data.cause: The Cluster Logger Service could not get the security keys due a wallet read failure.
data.action: Run the 'crsctl query wallet -type MGMTDB' command to verify that the wallet exists. If the problem persists, contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: The Cluster Logger Service was not able to connect to the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository because a Cluster Synchronization Services request failed.
data.cause: An attempt to connect to the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository failed due to a Cluster Synchronization Services failure.
data.action: If the problem persists, run 'diagcollection.pl' and contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: The System Monitor Service on this host is unable to communicate with the Cluster Logger Service on host %s, and will log the Cluster Health Analysis data to the local repository.
data.cause: Communication was lost with the Cluster Logger Service node.
data.action:
Verify all network connections between cluster nodes and repair
any problematic connections. If network problems are not found,
execute the following steps:
1. Run diagcollection.pl.
2. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The Cluster Health Analysis local repository is disabled on host %s. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: An internal error occurred while writing to the Cluster Health Analysis local repository.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: The Cluster Logger Service was unable to reset the password for Cluster Health Monitor.
data.cause: A password reset failure occurred when the Cluster Logger Service tried to reset the Cluster Health Monitor password after finding that the password had expired.
data.action: Run the 'srvctl config mgmtdb' command to verify that Grid Infrastructure Management Repository has been created successfully. If not, run the 'mgmtca setpasswd -user CHM' command to reset the password for Cluster Health Monitor. If the problem persists, run 'diagcollection.pl' and contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: The Cluster Logger Service was unable to reset the password for Cluster Health Analysis.
data.cause: A password reset failure occurred when the Cluster Logger Service tried to reset the Cluster Health Analysis password after finding that the password had expired.
data.action: Run the 'srvctl config mgmtdb' command to verify that Grid Infrastructure Management Repository has been created successfully. If not, run the 'mgmtca setpasswd -user CHA' command to reset the password for Cluster Health Analysis. If the problem persists, run 'diagcollection.pl' and contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: The Grid Infrastructure Management Repository exceeded the size set for it; disabling logging.
data.cause: An internal error caused the size of the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository to be reset to an unexpectedly large value. Logging was disabled to prevent further problems.
data.action:
Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: invalid cluster name '%s' specified
data.cause: An invalid cluster name was supplied to the CRSCTL utility.
data.action:
Specify a cluster name which is at least one character but no more
than 15 characters in length. The cluster name must be alphanumeric,
it cannot begin with a numeric character, and it may contain
hyphen (-) characters. However, it cannot end with a hyphen (-)
character.

data.message: invalid node name '%s' specified
data.cause: An invalid node name was supplied to the CRSCTL utility.
data.action:
Specify a node name which is at least one character but no more
than 63 characters in length. The node name must be alphanumeric,
it cannot begin with a numeric character, and it may contain
hyphen (-) characters. However, it cannot end with a hyphen (-)
character.

data.cause: An invalid client ID was supplied to the CRSCTL utility.
data.action: The client ID can be obtained by running the command 'crsctl get\nclientid dhcp'.

data.message: The OCR location %s is inaccessible. Details in %s.
data.cause: An error occurred while accessing the OCR.
data.action:
Use the ocrcheck command to validate the accessibility of the
device and its block integrity. Check that the OCR location in
question has the correct permissions. Determine whether this
behavior is limited to one node or whether it occurs across all of
the nodes in the cluster.
Use the ocrconfig command with the -replace option to replace
the OCR location.

data.cause: Error in communicating to the OCR server on a peer node. This OCR\ndid not receive a notification regarding its peer's death within\nthe specified time.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The OCR configuration is invalid. Details in %s.
data.cause: The OCR configuration on this node does not match the OCR\nconfiguration on the other nodes in the cluster.
data.action:
Determine the OCR configuration on the other nodes in the cluster
on which Oracle Clusterware is running by using the ocrcheck
command. Run the ocrconfig command with the -repair option to
correct the OCR configuration on this node.

data.message: The OCR mirror location %s was removed.
data.cause: The OCR location was successfully removed as requested by the user.
data.action: None.

data.message: OCR cannot determine that the OCR content contains the latest updates. Details in %s.
data.cause: The OCR could not be started. The OCR location configured on this\nnode does not have the necessary votes and might not have the\nlatest updates.
data.action:
Ensure that the other nodes in the cluster have the same OCR
location configured. If the configuration on the other nodes in
the cluster does not match, then run the ocrconfig command with
the -repair option to correct the configuration on this node.
If the configurations on all of the nodes match, use the ocrdump
command to ensure that the existing OCR location has the latest
updates. Run the ocrconfig command with the -overwrite option to
correct the problem. If the se procedures do not correct the
problem, then contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The OCR service started on node %s.
data.cause: The OCR was successfully started.
data.action: None.

data.message: The OCR location in an ASM disk group is inaccessible. Details in %s.
data.cause: An error occurred while accessing the OCR file in an ASM disk group.
data.action:
Use the 'asmcmd' command to verify if the ASM instance is active.
If the ASM instance aborted, it will be restarted automatically.
Use 'ocrcheck -config' to discover the OCR locations configured,
and verify using 'asmcmd' that the disk group in question is
mounted. Mount the disk group if it is not mounted. Validate if
the behavior is limited to one node or whether it occurs across
all of the nodes in the cluster. If nothing works, use the
'ocrconfig' command with the '-replace' or '-delete' option
to replace or remove the OCR location.

data.action: Check availability of the cluster registry and the details of the\nfailure from the log file

data.message: A request to terminate the Cluster Ready Service on node %s completed successfully. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The Cluster Ready Service on the above listed node did not respond to an earlier\nrequest within the specified time. The Cluster Ready Service will be terminated to\nprevent any possible cluster hangs.
data.action:
Check the Oracle Clusterware alert log on the listed node for any problems. Check
for any reason that might not allow the Cluster Ready Service to run optimally
on the listed node. Verify network accessibility to the listed node from other nodes
in the cluster. If the problem persists, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The Cluster Ready Service on this node terminated because it detected a failure while upgrading the Oracle Cluster Registry format. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The Cluster Ready Service on the node coordinating the upgrade of\nthe Oracle Cluster Registry format terminated.
data.action:
The Oracle Cluster Registry format upgrade will be completed
by another node in the cluster. The Cluster Ready Service on the
node listed above will be automatically restarted, and will be
able to function as soon as the upgrade completes. If the problem
persists, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The Cluster Ready Service on this node terminated because it was unable to open the import file while upgrading the Oracle Cluster Registry format. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: There was a failure accessing the import file on this node. The\nCluster Ready Service on this node may not have been active during\nthe Oracle Cluster Registry format upgrade.
data.action:
The Oracle Cluster Registry format upgrade will be completed
by another node in the cluster. The Cluster Ready Service on this
node will be automatically restarted, and will be able to function
as soon as the upgrade completes. If the problem persists, contact
Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Automatically repaired invalid Oracle Cluster Registry configuration on this node.  Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The OCR configuration on this node did not match with the OCR\nconfiguration on the other nodes in the cluster; therefore, it was\nautomatically repaired.
data.action: If this occurs repeatedly, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The OCR Service exited on host %s. Details in %s
data.cause: The OCR Service exited due to an internal error.
data.action: Determine whether the service has restarted. Collect Clusterware\nalert log and the CRSD log indicated in the message and contact\nOracle Support Services.

data.message: The Oracle Cluster Registry has invalid contents. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Some of the Oracle Cluster Registry contents were invalid.
data.action:
Check the log file indicated in the message for more details. Use
the 'ocrcheck' command to detect errors, and the 'ocrdump' command
to review the registry contents. If problems exist, the registry may
need to be recovered or restored. If the problem persists, contact
Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The Oracle Cluster Registry backup file in an ASM disk group is inaccessible. Details in %s.
data.cause: Oracle Cluster Registry backup location did not exists, wasn't\nmounted correctly, or did not have the required permissions.
data.action:
Ensure that the backup location exists, that it is mounted correctly
and visible to all nodes in the cluster, and that its permissions
are correct. Check the ASM entries in the alert log file for more
details.

data.message: Oracle Clusterware was forcibly upgraded without upgrading nodes %s. Version has changed from [%u, %s] to [%u, %s]. Details in %s.
data.cause: Oracle Clusterware was forcibly upgraded when the above listed\nnodes were not upgraded.
data.action: Delete the above listed nodes using the procedure documented in\nthe Oracle Clusterware documentation. If the nodes later become\naccessible, they can be added back into the cluster.

data.message: The Cluster Ready Service on this node terminated because the ASM instance was not active on this node. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The Cluster Ready Service on the node terminated because the\nASM instance was no longer active.
data.action: The Cluster Ready Services on this node will be automatically\nrestarted. If the problem persists, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Oracle Clusterware was upgraded to version [%s] on all nodes, but the cluster active version is still [%s]. Details in [%s].
data.cause: The cluster upgrade did not complete because the root upgrade script\nfailed on the last node, the root upgrade script was interrupted by\nthe user, or the cluster upgrade is ongoing.
data.action:
Check the Oracle Clusterware alert log on all nodes for any
problems. Rerun the root upgrade script on the last node to
completion, and ensure that the cluster active version has
changed using the 'crsctl query crs activeversion' command. If the
problem persists, run diagcollection.pl and contact Oracle Support
Services.

data.message: Oracle Clusterware patch has completed. The patch level has changed from [%u] to [%u]. Details in %s.
data.cause: The Oracle Clusterware was successfully patched.
data.action: None.

data.message: The Oracle Cluster Registry (OCR) location in an ASM disk group [%s] does not have sufficient space. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Unable to increase the size of OCR file in the above listed disk\ngroup as the disk group was out of space.
data.action:
Delete unused files from the disk group or add additional disks to
the disk group. Refer to Oracle Clusterware administration
documentation to know about the space requirements for OCR in ASM
disk group.

data.message: The Oracle Cluster Registry backup location %s is inaccessible from node %s. Details in %s.
data.cause: The backup location provided did not exist, was not\nmounted correctly, or did not have the required permissions.
data.action:
Ensure that the backup location exists, that it is mounted
correctly and visible to all nodes in the cluster, and that the
permissions are correct. If the backup location is an
ASM disk group, check the ASM entries in the alert log file for
more details.

data.message: The Oracle Cluster Registry backup file %s is corrupt. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The backup file created by the periodic backup of the Oracle Cluster\nRegistry (OCR) failed to pass the post-backup sanity check.\nEither the OCR was corrupted or the backup was faulty.
data.action:
If the fault was introduced during the backup generation, then it
will be corrected during the next backup generation, and no action
is required. If the subsequent backup is also faulty, then the
Oracle Cluster Registry might be corrupt. Contact Oracle
Support Services.

data.message: Cluster Ready Service failed to retrieve user information. Details at %s in %s.

data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The Oracle Cluster Registry backup file %s could not be validated. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The indicated Oracle Cluster Registry (OCR) backup file\ncould not be validated due to validation process not starting or\nfailing to run the validation check.
data.action:
If the backup was attempted as part of an automatic periodic backup,
then no action is needed. If the backup was attempted as part of a
manual backup, then try the backup again.
If the problem persists, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Error upgrading the active version of Oracle Clusterware.\\n
data.cause: An attempt was made to change the Oracle Clusterware active\nversion before all nodes were upgraded.
data.action: Run root.sh script on all nodes in the cluster. If the problem\npersists, contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: Started to upgrade the active version of Oracle Clusterware. This operation may take a few minutes.\\n
Unable to complete Oracle Clusterware upgrade while nodes %s have not yet upgraded.\\n
data.cause:
An attempt was made to change the Oracle Clusterware active
version before all known nodes had been upgraded. Note that some of
the nodes listed in the message may no longer be current or recent
cluster members.
data.action:
Issue the 'olsnodes' command to list current and recent cluster
members.  Any nodes listed in the error message, but not listed by
'olsnodes' have not been active recently, and should be deleted
using the procedure documented in the Oracle Clusterware
documentation.
The currently or recently active cluster members listed by
'olsnodes' should be upgraded, or, if no longer needed, deleted:
1) Run the rootupgrade.sh script on each node to be retained.
2) Delete nodes no longer desired using the procedure
documented in the Oracle Clusterware documentation.
Once all of the nodes listed in the message have been upgraded or
deleted, run the rootupgrade.sh script on an upgraded node to
complete the upgrade.
If one or more nodes could not upgraded or deleted, forcibly
upgrade the cluster using the procedure documented in the
Oracle Clusterware documentation.

data.message: Attempting to forcibly upgrade the active version of Oracle Clusterware using only the nodes %s.\\n
Oracle Clusterware was forcibly upgraded without upgrading nodes %s.\\n
data.cause: Oracle Clusterware was forcibly upgraded when the above listed\nnodes were not upgraded.
data.action:
Delete the above listed nodes using the procedure documented in
the Oracle Clusterware documentation. If the nodes later become
accessible, they can be added back into the cluster.

data.message: Error while setting up user interface server. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Oracle High Availability Service encountered communication error.
data.action: This is an internal error. Contact Oracle Support Services..

data.message: Error while listening for events. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Oracle High Availability Service encountered communication error.
data.action: This is an internal error. Contact Oracle Support Services..

data.message: Oracle High Availability Services aborted due to internal error.
data.cause: Fatal Internal Error. Check the Oracle High Availability Service log file to determine the cause.
data.action: Determine whether the Oracle High Availability Service gets auto-started.

data.message: Failed to open key '%s' in OLR. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: This is an internal error.
data.action: This is an internal error. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Could not get security attribute for system key '%s' in OLR. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Encountered error while reading system key attributes in OLR.
data.action: This is an internal error. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Failed to initialize batch handler for OLR. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Could not initialize batch handler for multiwrite in OLR.
data.action: This is an internal error. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Encountered error while setting key value for key '%s' in OLR. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Encountered an error while executing a batch write in OLR.
data.action: This is an internal error. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Error while executing batch for multi writes in OLR. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Encountered an error while executing a batch write in OLR.
data.action: This is an internal error. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Error enumerating subkeys for key '%s' in OLR. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Encountered an error while reading subkey values in OLR.
data.action: This is an internal error. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Failed to retrieve the maximum value supported in OLR. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Could not read the maximum value size from registry.
data.action: This is an internal error. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Failed to add a delete key operation for key '%s' to a batch in OLR. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Encountered internal error while deleting key in OLR.
data.action: This is an internal error. Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Oracle High Availability Service aborted due to an unexpected error [%s]. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: Look at the associated error message to fix the underlying issue.
data.action: If the problem persists, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: A failure occurred in the CSS daemon during initialization; Details at %s in %s
data.cause: A fatal error occurred during the initialization of the CSS daemon.
data.action:
Check for prior errors logged in the alert log. Correct any
errors that can be corrected.  If there are no errors shown,
or the errors cannot be resolved, contact Oracle Support
Services

data.message: Node '%s' has a pending role change; Oracle High Availability Services needs to be restarted.
data.cause: A 'crsctl stop cluster' command was run after a node's role has changed.

data.message: EVMD started on node %s.
data.cause: EVMD has started either because of a CRS start, a node reboot,\nor an EVMD restart.
data.action: None required. You can run the 'crsctl check evmd' command to validate the health of EVMD.

data.message: EVMD aborted on node %s. Error [%s]. Details in %s.
data.cause: EVMD has aborted due to an internal error. Check the EVMD log file\nto determine the cause.
data.action: Determine whether the EVMD is auto-started and contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The Event Management Service terminated on node %s. Listening port %d is in use by another application. Details in %s.
data.cause: The Event Management Service has aborted because the\nconfigured listening port is being used by another\napplication on this node.

data.message: CSSD Reconfiguration complete. Active nodes are %s.
data.cause: A node joined or left the cluster.
data.action: None.

data.message: CSSD aborted on node %s. Error [%s]; details in %s.
data.cause: The CSS daemon aborted on the listed node with the listed return\ncode.
data.action: Collect the CSS daemon logs from all nodes and any CSS daemon core\nfiles and contact Oracle Support.

data.message: CSSD on node %s has been shut down.
data.cause: The CSS daemon on the listed node was terminated.
data.action: None.

data.message: CSSD voting file is offline: %s; details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The indicated voting file became unusable on the local node either\nbecause it was being replaced or because it was not accessible.
data.action:
1. No action necessary if the voting file was replaced.
2. If the voting file was not replaced then verify that the
filesystem containing the indicated voting file is
available on the local node.

data.message: CSSD voting file is online: %s; details in %s.
data.cause: The CSS daemon has detected a valid configured voting file.
data.action: None.

data.message: The number of voting files available, %d, is less than the minimum number of voting files required, %d, resulting in CSSD termination to ensure data integrity; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The number of voting files has decreased to a number of files\nthat is insufficient.
data.action: Locate previous 1604, 1613, 1614 and 1615 messages and take\naction as indicated by those messages.

data.message: Node %s is being evicted in cluster incarnation %d; details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The local node has detected that the indicated node is still\nactive, but not able to communicate with this node, so is\nforcibly removing the indicated node from the cluster.
data.action: Collect the CSS daemon logs from all nodes and any CSS daemon core\nfiles and contact Oracle Support.

data.message: This node was evicted by node %d, %s; details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The local node was evicted by the indicated node.
data.action: Collect the CSS daemon logs from all nodes and any CSS daemon core\nfiles and contact Oracle Support.

data.message: This node is unable to communicate with other nodes in the cluster and is going down to preserve cluster integrity; details at %s in %s.
data.cause:
Communication was lost with some nodes of the cluster and this
node detected that another sub-cluster was designated to be the
surviving sub-cluster. This node went down to preserve data
integrity.
data.action:
Verify all network connections between cluster nodes and
repair any problematic connections. If there do not appear
to be any network problems,
1. collect the CSS daemon logs, system messages and
any CSS daemon core files from all nodes and
2. contact Oracle Support.

data.message: Network communication with node %s (%d) missing for 90%% of timeout interval.  Removal of this node from cluster in %d.%03d seconds
data.cause: Did not receive heartbeat messages from the node. This could be\ndue to network problems or failure of the listed node.
data.action:
Check if the private interconnect network used by cluster is
functioning properly, including all the cables, network cards,
switches/routers etc. between this node and listed node. Correct
any problems discovered.

data.message: Network communication with node %s (%d) missing for 75%% of timeout interval.  Removal of this node from cluster in %d.%03d seconds
data.cause: Did not receive heartbeat messages from the node. This could be\ndue to network problems or failure of the listed node.
data.action:
Check if the private interconnect network used by cluster is
functioning properly, including all the cables, network cards,
switches/routers etc. between this node and listed node. Correct
any problems discovered.

data.message: Network communication with node %s (%d) missing for 50%% of timeout interval.  Removal of this node from cluster in %d.%03d seconds
data.cause: Did not receive heartbeat messages from the node. This could be\ndue to network problems or failure of listed node.
data.action:
Check if the private interconnect network used by cluster is
functioning properly, including all the cables, network cards,
switches/routers etc. between this node and listed node. Correct
any problems discovered.

data.message: No I/O has completed after 90%% of the maximum interval. Voting file %s will be considered not functional in %d milliseconds
data.cause: Voting device I/O has not completed for a long time. This could be due\nsome error with the device the voting file is on or in some element\nin the path of the I/O to the device.
data.action:
Verify that the device is working properly including all elements
in the I/O path. The voting file listed will be considered inactive
in the number of milliseconds specified. Failure of a majority of
devices will result in node reboot.

data.message: No I/O has completed after 75%% of the maximum interval. Voting file %s will be considered not functional in %d milliseconds
data.cause: Voting device I/O has not completed for a long time. This could be due\nsome error with the device the voting file is on or in some element\nin the path of the I/O to the device.
data.action:
Verify that the device is working properly including all elements
in the I/O path. The voting file listed will be considered inactive
in the number of milliseconds specified. Failure of a majority of
devices will result in node reboot.

data.message: No I/O has completed after 50%% of the maximum interval. Voting file %s will be considered not functional in %d milliseconds
data.cause: Voting device I/O has not completed for a long time. This could be due\nsome error with the device the voting file is on or in some element\nin the path of the I/O to the device.
data.action:
Verify that the device is working properly including all elements
in the I/O path. The voting file listed will be considered inactive
in the number of milliseconds specified. Failure of a majority of
devices will result in node reboot.

data.message: invalid component key name <%s> used
data.cause: the given component key name could not be recognized.
data.action: re-run the command with a valid component key name.

data.message: invalid message type <%d> used
data.cause: an unrecognized message type was sent.
data.action: Retry with a valid command again.

data.message: The BMC device used for IPMI at IP address %s is not properly configured for ADMIN access; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The IPMI BMC is not configured to support the ADMIN access methods\nrequired by Oracle Clusterware.
data.action:
Consult the clusterware admin manual for proper procedures in
configuring BMC. Use the BMC configuration tool (ipmitool
or ipmiutil) command to check and verify
that the current configuration supports either MD5 or password
validation for ADMIN access.

data.message: The information required to do node kill for node %s is incomplete; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Incomplete config information stored in Cluster Registry for node\nkill.
data.action: Make sure all the information pertaining to the node kill method

data.message: The requested node kill information change could not be validated by node %s; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Unable to validate the node kill information for this node.
data.action: Additional information can be found in the CRS alert log of\nthe node that performed the validation.\n

data.message: The node kill information of node %s could not be validated by this node due to failure in connecting to the IPMI device; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Unable to validate the node kill information for this node.
data.action: Additional information can be found in the CSSD logs.\n

data.message: The node kill information of node %s could not be validated by this node due to invalid authorization information; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Unable to validate the kill information for this node.
data.action: Additional information can be found in the CSSD logs.\n

data.message: The IPMI configuration data for this node stored in the Oracle registry is incomplete; details at %s in %s
data.cause: All the necessary information such as IPMI username, password and\nIP address are not present.
data.action:
Make sure all the information(BMC IPMI username, password and
IP address) are present. Use commands 'crsctl set css ipmiaddr'
and 'crsctl set css ipmiadmin' for this.

data.message: The IPMI node kill information could not be validated due to inability to connect to the IPMI device at BMC IP address provided %s; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Unable to validate the BMC IPMI IP address provided.
data.action: Additional information can be found in the CSSD logs.\n

data.message: The IPMI node kill information of BMC at IP address %s could not be validated due to invalid authorization information. The BMC username provided is '%s'; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Unable to validate the BMC IPMI UserName and password provided.
data.action: Additional information can be found in the CSSD logs.\n

data.message: The requested Node kill information change succeeds vacuously because there is no other node in cluster to validate.
data.cause: Unable to validate the credentials because this is the sole node in\nthe cluster.
data.action: To complete the valdidation, shut down the clusterware stack on\nthis node, start another node and restart the stack on this node.\n

data.message: Node %s, number %d, was shut down
A Configuration change request completed successfully
A Configuration change request failed because another configuration change is in progress; Details at %s in %s
A Configuration change request failed because read of existing voting files failed; Details at %s in %s
A Configuration change request failed because write to new voting files failed; Details at %s in %s
A configuration change request failed because not all the new voting files were discovered; Details at %s in %s
data.cause: One or more of the voting files being added were not discovered.\nMessage 1638 identifies the unique ID(s) of the file(s) that\ncould not be found.
data.action:
Verify if the discovery string is adequate to discover the new
voting files. If not, modify discovery string using command
'crsctl replace discoverystring xxxxx'.

data.message: A configuration change request failed because one or more nodes are not a sufficient Clusterware version level; Details at %s in %s
data.cause: One ore more nodes are not a sufficient version level.
data.action: Configuration change would not be successful until all nodes are at\nat the latest version. Try after all the nodes are upgraded.\n

data.message: Node %s is being removed from the cluster in cluster incarnation %d
data.cause: The local node is removing the indicated node from the cluster\nbecause it appears to be dead.
data.action:
Verify that the node that was removed, or the Oracle Clusterware
on that node, was down.  The CRS alert log of the node that was
removed has information regarding why the node, or clusterware
on the node, was no longer active.  If the node was still up
and Oracle Clusterware still active on that node, collect the
CSS daemon logs from all nodes and any CSS daemon core files
and contact Oracle Support.

data.message: CSSD failed to register group %s in vendor clusterware; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The local node is not able to register the group of\nvendor clusterware.
data.action: Verify that the vendor clusterware is installed and configured correctly.\n

data.message: CSSD is unable to determine cluster name; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Name of the cluster cannot be determined from configuration.
data.action: Verify that Oracle Clusterware installation was successful.\n

data.message: CSSSD failed to initialize vendor clusterware; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The local node is not able to attach vendor clusterware.
data.action: Verify that the vendor clusterware is installed and configured correctly.\n

data.message: The CSS daemon was started in exclusive mode but found an active CSS daemon on node %s and is terminating; details at %s in %s
data.cause:
The CSS daemon was started in exclusive mode, which requires
that the clusterware stack is down on all other nodes to ensure
data integrity.  A CSS daemon was detected on another node,
so the CSS daemon on this node is terminating.
data.action: Stop the Oracle clusterware stack that is running on the\nindicated node.\n

data.message: Unable to locate configured voting file with ID %s; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The voting file with unique the ID indicated in the message\nwas not found during the voting file discovery phase of CSS\ninitialization.
data.action:
Verify that all configured voting files are accessible on this
node.  Any voting files that are not accessible should be
removed and replaced with accessible voting files using the
appropriate 'crsctl' commands.

data.message: Unable to locate voting file with ID %s that is being added to the list of configured voting files; details at %s in %s
data.cause:
The voting file with the unique ID indicated in the message
was not found during the voting file discovery phase of CSS
initialization.  This voting file is in the process of being
added to the list of configured voting files.
data.action:
Verify that all voting files to be added are accessible on this
node.  Any voting files that are not accessible should be
removed and replaced with accessible voting files using the
appropriate 'crsctl' commands.

data.message: Rejecting configuration change %u:%u because another configuration change is already in progress; details at %s in %s
data.cause: A configuration change was requested, but another configuration\nchange is already in progress and only one configuration change\nmay be processed at a time.
data.action: Wait for the current configuration change to complete, then\nresubmit this configuration change.\n

data.message: Value '%d' must be in the '%d' - '%d' range
data.cause: The value is not within the allowed range.
data.action: Use a proper value.

data.message: Rejecting configuration change %u:%u because one or more new voting files in the new configuration could not be found; details at %s in %s
data.cause: A configuration change that involved the addition of voting\nfiles is being rejected because some of the new voting files\nwere not located.
data.action:
Verify that the voting file name is correct and that it is
accessible on this node, if the voting files are not managed
by ASM.  Message number 1638 provides greater detail.

data.message: Rejecting configuration change %u:%u because only %u of the required %u voting files of the new configuration were located; details at %s in %s
data.cause:
A configuration change that involved a change to the list of
voting files is being rejected because a sufficient number
of voting files in the new configuration could not be
located.
data.action: Verify that all voting files in the new configuration\nare accessible on this node.\n

data.message: Node %d is using a different CSS configuration from the one used by this node; this node is terminating to preserve integrity; details at %s in %s
data.cause:
Another node in the cluster is using a different set of
CSS configuration values, such as misscount or voting files.
Inconsistency can result in data corruption, so this node is
terminating to avoid data corruption.
data.action:
Collect Clusterware alert log and the CSSD log indicated in
the message as well as the CSS daemon logs of all other nodes
in the cluster and contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Failed to format the CSS voting disk %s
data.cause: Problems were encountered attempting to access the voting file.
data.action: Verify that the voting file can be accessed, the file exists,\nhas the proper ownership and permissions, etc.\n

data.message: The initialization of the EXADATA fencing facility failed in start with error ORA-%d; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The start of the initialization of the EXADATA fencing facility\nfailed with the error code shown.
data.action: See the Action section of the error message shown.\n

data.message: The initialization of the EXADATA fencing facility failed in completion with error ORA-%d; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The completion of the initialization of the EXADATA fencing\nfacility failed with the error code shown.
data.action: See the Action section of the error message shown.\n

data.message: Creation of a EXADATA fence identifier failed with error ORA-%d; details at %s in %s
data.cause: An attempt to create an identifier for a fence to an EXADATA\ndevice failed with the error code shown.
data.action: See the Action section of the error message shown.\n

data.message: Initialization of a EXADATA fence failed with error ORA-%d; details at %s in %s
data.cause: An attempt to initiate a fence to an EXADATA device failed with\nthe error code shown.
data.action: See the Action section of the error message shown.\n

data.message: Completion of queued EXADATA fence requests failed with error ORA-%d; details at %s in %s
data.cause: Previously queued fence requests to an EXADATA device failed with\nthe error code shown.
data.action: See the Action section of the error message shown.\n

data.message: An I/O error occurred for voting file: %s; details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The listed voting file became inaccessible.
data.action: Verify that the filesystem containing the listed voting file is\navailable on the local node.\n

data.message: Configuration change %u:%u rejected by node %u %s; details at %s in %s
data.cause: A new configuration change request from this node was not\naccepted due to another node rejecting the change.
data.action: Check the CRS alert log of the node rejecting this configuration\nchange for more details.\n

data.message: Configuration change %u:%u rejected because it would make the active version of node %u lower than the current setting %s of this node; details at %s in %s
data.cause: A new configuration change request from another node was not\naccepted because the new Active Version in the request is lower\nthan this node's Active Version.
data.action: Ensure that the new Active Version is not lower than the current\nActive Version of the nodes in the cluster.\n

data.message: Starting clean up of CRSD resources.
data.cause: Clean up of the resources registered in CRSD started.
data.action: None\n

data.message: The clean up of the CRSD resources failed.
data.cause: Clean up of the resources registered in CRSD failed.
data.action: Check the CRS alert log.\n

data.message: Clean up of CRSD resources finished successfully.
data.cause: Clean up of the resources registered in CRSD finished.
data.action: None\n

data.message: CSSD on node %s detected a problem and started to shutdown.
data.cause: The CSS daemon on the listed node detected a problem and started to shutdown.
data.action: Check the CRS alert log.\n

data.message: The CSS daemon is terminating due to a fatal error; Details at %s in %s
data.cause: A fatal error occurred during CSS daemon processing.
data.action:
Check for prior errors logged in the alert log. Correct any
errors that can be corrected.  If there are no errors shown,
or the errors cannot be resolved, contact Oracle support

data.message: Unable to obtain the voting file discovery string; Details at %s in %s
data.cause: An attempt to obtain the voting file discovery string from\nthe profile failed, causing the CSS daemon to fail.
data.action:
Collect the Clusterware alert log and the CSSD log of this
node as well as all CSS daemon logs of all other nodes in the
cluster and contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: There is a mismatch of the initial cluster incarnation among the cluster nodes; Details at %s in %s
data.cause: An internal error occurred.
data.action:
Collect the Clusterware alert log and the CSSD log of this
node as well as all CSS daemon logs of all other nodes in the
cluster and contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: An attempt to kill node %s failed; Details at %s in %s
data.cause: To protect data integrity a node kill was attempted for\nthe indicated node, but it failed.
data.action:
Collect the Clusterware alert log and the CSSD log of this
node as well as the CSS daemon logs of all other nodes in the
cluster and contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: The CSS daemon shutdown has completed
data.cause: A command to shut down the CSS daemon was issued by a user\nand the shutdown processing is completed.  The CSS daemon\nis terminated.
data.action: No action is required.\n

data.message: The CSS daemon is not responding. Reboot will occur in %d milliseconds; Details at %s in %s
data.cause: The CSS daemon is failing to respond.
data.action:
Collect the Clusterware alert log and the CSSD log of this
node as well as the CSS daemon logs of all other nodes in the
cluster and contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Member kill requested by node %s for member number %d, group %s
data.cause: A request to kill a member of the indicated group\nwas issued by a process on the indicated node.
data.action: No action is required.\n

data.message: Member kill issued by PID %s for %d members, group %s. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: A member kill request was issued by the indicated process\nfor the members belonging to the indicated group.
data.action: No action is required.

data.message: No voting files found; switching node role to 'leaf'.
data.cause: A node attempting to start as a Hub node was not able to find a voting file.
data.action: No action is required.

data.message: The CSS daemon cannot join the cluster because the software version %s is lower than the active version %s; Details at %s in %s
data.cause: The cluster has been upgraded to the active version indicated.\nin the message, but this node is at a lower software version,\nas indicated in the message.
data.action: Upgrade this node to the active version indicated in the message\n

data.message: maximum number of cluster Hub nodes reached; the CSS daemon is terminating
data.cause: A node attempting to start as a Hub node found the maximum number\nof Hub nodes already active.
data.action:
If the configured node role is 'auto', no action is required
for the node to restart as a Leaf node.  If the configured
node role is 'hub', then the configured role must be changed
to a Leaf node using 'crsctl set node role leaf' or the Hub size
must be increased using 'crsctl set cluster hubsize'.

data.message: no Hub nodes found; switching node role to 'hub'
data.cause: A node attempting to start as a Leaf node was unable to locate any Hub nodes.
data.action: No action is required.

data.message: node %s not allowed to join because the maximum number of Hub nodes has been reached
data.cause: A node attempting to start as a Hub node found the maximum number\nof Hub nodes already active.
data.action: No action is required.

data.message: operation is not allowed on a Leaf node\\n
data.cause: An unsupported operation was requested on a Leaf node.
data.action: Retry this operation on a Hub node.

data.message: The number of voting files available %d is less than the minimum number of voting files required %d.
data.cause: The number of voting files has decreased to a number of files\nthat is insufficient.
data.action: Look in the alert log for related messages such as 1714,\n1604, 1613, 1614 and 1615 and act accordingly.

data.message: Leaf node could not find any Hub nodes to connect to; details at %s in %s
data.cause: A Leaf node attempted to join the cluster but could not find a\nHub node to which to connect.
data.action:
Verify that the clusterware stack is up and running on at least
one Hub node and, if not, start the stack on one or more Hub nodes.
Verify that the Grid Naming Service (GNS) resource is active on a Hub node.
If not, start it on at least one node. Check if the network connectivity
is viable to all Hub nodes that have the clusterware stack running.
If the Leaf node startup has exhausted its retry attempts, it may be
necessary to start the clusterware stack manually on the Leaf node.
Contact Oracle Support Services if all of the above is verified
and the Leaf node is not able to find any Hub nodes to which to
to connect.

data.message: The value for parameter %s is outside the allowed range of %d to %d\\n
data.cause: An attempt was made to set a parameter with invalid value.
data.action: Set the parameter with a value in the indicated range.\n

data.message: The number of voting files currently available %d has fallen to the minimum number of voting files required %d.
data.cause:
The Cluster Synchronization Service daemon (CSSD) has detected that
the number of voting files currently available is equal to the
minimum number of voting files required on the node. There is risk
of node eviction in the case of another voting disk failure.
data.action:
Restore access to voting files or configure additional voting disks
so that the number of voting files currently available is
more than the minimum number of voting files required.

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

data.message: Initialization of the required component GIPC failed; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The initialization of the communications component GIPC failed,\ncausing the CSSD startup to fail.
data.action: Collect alert log and the CSSD log indicated in the message\nand contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: Initialization of the required component OLR failed; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The initialization of the local repository component OLR failed,\ncausing the CSSD startup to fail.
data.action: Collect clusterware alert log and daemon logs and contact\nOracle Support Services.\n

data.message: Initialization of the required component GPNP failed because the GPNP server daemon is not up; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The initialization of the configuration profile service failed\nbecause the associated server is not up, causing the CSSD\nstartup to fail.
data.action: Collect clusterware alert log and daemon logs and contact\nOracle Support Services.\n

data.message: Initialization of the required component %s failed; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The initialization of a component required by the CSS daemon\nfailed, causing the CSSD startup to fail
data.action: Collect clusterware alert log and daemon logs and contact\nOracle Support Services.\n

data.message: Found %d configured voting files but %d voting files are required, terminating to ensure data integrity; details at %s in %s
data.cause: The voting file discovery was unable to locate a sufficient\nnumber of valid voting files to guarantee data integrity and\nis terminating to avoid potential data corruption.
data.action:
Delete the voting files that are no longer available, as
indicated by message number 1637, using appropriate 'crsctl'
commands, run either on another node where the clusterware
stack is active, or by starting the clusterware stack in
exclusive mode.

data.message: Found %d of %d voting files in a pending configuration change but %d voting files are required, terminating to ensure data integrity; details at %s in %s
data.cause:
The voting file discovery was unable to locate a sufficient
number of voting files from the new configuration when a
configuration change to add or delete voting files is in
progress.  The CSS daemon is terminating to avoid potential
data corruption.
data.action:
Delete the voting files that are no longer available, as
indicated by message number 1638, using appropriate 'crsctl'
commands, run either on another node where the clusterware
stack is active, or by starting the clusterware stack in
exclusive mode.

data.message: Lease acquisition for node %s number %d completed
data.cause: CSSD acquired a node number through a lease acquisition procedure.
data.action: None\n

data.message: Lease acquisition failed for node %s because all lease slots are in use; Details at %s in %s
data.cause: The node failed to acquire a lease because all the lease slots\nwere found to be occupied by other nodes.
data.action: Using olsnodes command get the list of leased nodes.\nDelete the unused nodes using appropriate crsctl command.\n

data.message: Lease acquisition failed for node %s because no voting file has been configured; Details at %s in %s
data.cause: At least one voting file is required for CSSD to function properly.\nNo voting files have been configured.
data.action: Add at lease one voting file using appropriate crsctl command.\n

data.message: Lease acquisition failed for node %s because CSSD failed to access majority of voting files; Details at %s in %s
data.cause: A majority of the voting files are not accessible by a node.
data.action:
Delete the voting files that are no longer available, as
indicated by message number 1637, using appropriate 'crsctl'
commands, run either on another node where the Clusterware
stack is active, or by starting the Clusterware stack in
exclusive mode.

data.message: Increasing the number of leases available for new nodes from %d to %d
data.cause: All the currently available leases are being used.\nHence the number of leases available are increased.
data.action: None\n

data.message: Failed to save the node number acquired for node %s; Details at %s in %s
data.cause:
CSSD failed to save the node number acquired during startup.
The node number is saved to speed up the subsequent startup.
Hence this is not a real problem but just a performance degradation
on the next startup.
data.action: Collect Clusterware alert log, CSSD logs and OHASD logs indicated\nin the message and contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: CSSD daemon is started in %s mode
data.cause: CSSD has been started on the node.
data.action: None\n

data.message: Unable to discover any voting files, retrying discovery in %d seconds; Details at %s in %s
The CSS daemon has detected a voting file add during startup and is waiting for the add to complete; Details at %s in %s
data.cause:
A voting file add started on another node is in progress while
this CSS daemon is starting.  To avoid the potential for data
corruption, the CSS daemon on this node must wait for the add
to complete.
data.action:
This is normally a temporary condition that is automatically
resolved. If the clusterware stack cannot start on any node,
this condition may be corrected by starting the clusterware
stack in exclusive mode using 'crsctl start crs -excl'
followed by 'crsctl stop crs' on one node.  This will
automatically correct the condition and the clusterware can
be started normally on all nodes.

data.message: The CSS daemon is unable to continue due to a failure in required component %s.
data.cause: A component required by the Cluster Synchronization Service\n(CSS) daemon has failed.  The CSS daemon is unable to\ncontinue and is failing.
data.action: See the alert log for more detailed messages indicating the\nnature of the problem and the location of additional\ninformation regarding this error.

data.message: Cluster Synchronization Service daemon (CSSD) %s not scheduled for %d msecs.
data.cause:
Excessive system load has prevented threads in the Cluster
Synchronization Service daemon (CSSD) from being scheduled for
execution for the time indicated in the message. This indicates
the system is overloaded.
data.action: Take steps to reduce the system load or increase system\nresources to handle the load.

data.message: Cluster Synchronization Services daemon (CSSD) is ready for operation.
data.cause:
Cluster Synchronization Services daemon (CSSD) is fully initialized
and functional. CSSD group membership services has started.
Services dependent on CSSD can start using cluster synchronization
services.
data.action: None.

data.message: Cluster Synchronization Service daemon (CSSD) was unable to complete initialization for fence type %s.
data.cause:
The Cluster Synchronization Service daemon (CSSD) failed to complete
initialization for the indicated fence type, most likely because of
a failure in the associated support entity. The entities CSSD
depends on are ASM, DISKMON. Messages in the alert log from DISKMON
or ASM may supply additional details.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Cluster Synchronization Service daemon encountered an internal error.
data.cause: CSSD failed due to an internal error.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Cluster Synchronization Services daemon (CSSD) exited because it failed to spawn thread %s.
data.cause:
Cluster Synchronization Services failed to spawn the indicated
critical thread due to an operating system error.
The accompanying message provides additional details on
failed system call.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: CSSD agent failed to spawn CSSD process
data.cause: The Cluster Synchronization Services daemon could not be started\nbecause the operating system failed to spawn the process.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Encountered operating system error '%s' while performing operation '%s'.
data.cause: The operating system encountered an error for the indicated operation.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Process failed to run in real-time priority. Details at %s in %s.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Network communication between this node '%s' (%d) and node '%s' (%d) re-established. Node removal no longer imminent.
data.action: None.

data.message: The majority of voting files are accessible on %d sites, however %d sites are required, terminating to ensure data integrity; details at %s in %s
data.cause:
A check on voting file accessibility prompted by a voting file
management operation, periodic voting file access or lease
acquisition determined that a majority of voting files on a
majority of sites were not accessible by the local node.
data.action:
Delete the voting files that are no longer available, as
indicated by message CRS-01637, using the appropriate 'crsctl'
commands. Run the crsctl command either on another node where the
clusterware stack is active, or by starting the clusterware
stack in exclusive mode.

data.message: Cluster %s configured with nodes %s.

data.cause: The request for node number of this node failed.
data.action:
Verify that the CSS daemon is running and restart it if not
Retry the operation that failed after restart.
Look for error messages from the CSS daemon in the alert log
indicating any problems.

data.message: An internal cluster configuration command failed in an OCR/OLR operation. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: This is an internal error.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Node-specific configuration for node %s in Oracle Local Registry was upgraded to version %s.
data.cause: None.
data.action: None.

data.message: The cluster configuration command failed to open OCR or OLR key %s. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: An expected or required piece of configuration is missing from the\ncluster or local registry.
data.action:
Use the ocrcheck utility to detect errors, and the ocrdump utility
to review the registry contents. If problems exist, the registry may
need to be recovered or restored. If the problem persists, contact
Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Node-specific configuration for node %s in Oracle Local Registry was patched to patch level %u.
data.cause: None.
data.action: None.

data.message: Node %s patched to patch level %u.
data.cause: None.

data.cause: None.
data.action: None.
