data.action: Retry specifying a valid location.\n

data.message: Cluster Health Monitor repository size change completed on all nodes.
Cluster Health Monitor repository retention change failed on one or more nodes. Aborting retention change.
data.cause: An error occurred while setting Cluster Health Monitor repository size on the Cluster Logger Service.
data.action: Retry specifying a valid location.\n

data.message: Grid Infrastructure Management Repository configuration error \\n %s
data.cause: Grid Infrastructure Management Repository configuration error occurred.
data.action:
Take the following steps.
1) Examine the accompanying ORA-nnnnn or CRS-nnnn error messages. If possible, correct the issue reported.
2) Issue a 'srvctl status mgmtdb' command to determine the status of the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository database. If it is not online, examine the database instance alert log to determine what happened.
3) If you are unable to determine or correct the problem, run 'diagcollection.pl' and contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Grid Infrastructure Management Repository connection error \\n %s
data.cause: Grid Infrastructure Management Repository connection error occurred.
data.action:
Take the following steps.
1) Examine the accompanying ORA-nnnnn or CRS-nnnn error messages. If possible, correct the issue reported.
2) Issue a 'srvctl status mgmtdb' command to determine the status of the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository database. If it is not online, examine the database instance alert log to determine what happened.
3) If you are unable to determine or correct the problem, run 'diagcollection.pl' and contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Warning: %s option has been deprecated and will be ignored.
data.cause: A deprecated option was specified on the command line. The option\nwas ignored.
data.action: Check the documentation for the new syntax of the command.\n

data.message: oclumon was not able to connect to the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository because an authorization failure occurred. \\n%s
data.cause: An authorization failure occurred when connecting to the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository.
data.action: Run the 'srvctl config mgmtdb' command to verify that Grid Infrastructure Management Repository has been created successfully. If not, run the 'mgmtca' command to reset the passwords in the wallet. If the problem persists, run 'diagcollection.pl' and contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: oclumon was not able to connect to the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository because no listener was available.
data.cause: An attempt to connect to the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository failed because no Grid Infrastructure Management Repository listener was running.
data.action: Use the 'srvctl status mgmtlsnr' command to confirm that Grid Infrastructure Management Repository listener is running. If it is not, start it using the 'srvctl start mgmtlsnr' command. If the problem persists, run 'diagcollection.pl' and contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: oclumon was not able to retrieve the security keys from the wallet.
data.cause: An attempt to retrieve the security keys from the wallet failed.
data.action: Run the 'crsctl query wallet -type MGMTDB' command to verify that the wallet exists. If the problem persists, contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: oclumon was not able to connect to the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository because a Cluster Synchronization Services request failed.
data.cause: An attempt to connect to the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository failed due to a Cluster Synchronization Services failure.
data.action: If the problem persists, run 'diagcollection.pl' and contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: Cluster Health Monitor repository retention change failed. Aborting retention change. Error: %s
data.cause: An error occurred while setting the Cluster Health Monitor repository size on the cluster logger service.
data.action:
Take the following steps.
1) Examine the accompanying ORA-nnnnn or CRS-nnnn error messages. If possible, correct the issue reported.
2) Issue a 'srvctl status mgmtdb' command to determine the status of the Grid Infrastructure Management Repository database. If it is not online, examine the database instance alert log to determine what happened.
3) If you are unable to determine or correct the problem, run 'diagcollection.pl' and contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Error %s: Node name %s is unknown or invalid. No data found for this node in Grid Infrastructure Management Repository.
data.cause: The 'oclumon' command could not be carried out as entered because the node name cited in the message was invalid. The cited node name was ignored and the query executed with any remaining names.
data.action: Reissue the 'oclumon' command, if desired, supplying a valid name for the node name cited in the message. Refer to the product documentation or to command online help for information.\n

data.message: Cluster Health Monitor repository retention change failed. Error: retention space is lower than size permitted.
data.cause: An attempt to set the Cluster Health Monitor repository size on the cluster logger service was rejected because the specified size was smaller than the permitted minimum size.
data.action: Retry the command specifying a retention size larger or equal to the minimum size of 1 GB.\n

data.message: Error %s: Too many PIDs
data.cause: The command 'oclumon dumpnodeview -pid' failed because too many PIDs were specified.
data.action: Refer to the product documentation or to the command online help for information and reissue the command specifying a valid number of PIDs.\n

data.message: Error %s: Write operation is not permitted.
data.cause: The command 'oclumon dumpnodeview -dir <dir_name>' failed because the user was not allowed to write in the specified directory.
data.action: Ensure that the user has write permission for the specified directory and retry.\n

data.message: Error %s: Directory does not exist.
data.cause: The command 'oclumon dumpnodeview -dir <dir_name> failed because the specified directory did not exist.
data.action: Create the specified directory and retry.\n

data.message: Credential domain does not exist.
data.cause: The provided credential domain did not exist.
data.action: Specify another credential domain path or create the credential domain.

data.message: Error: 'dumpnodeview' option -v or -verbose conflicts with additional view options.
data.cause: The command 'oclumon dumpnodeview' failed because either -v or -verbose option was specified in addition to other view options (-system, -process, -cpu, etc.). The verbose options imply the inclusion of every part.
data.action:
Retry the operation specifying other options without -v or -verbose or specifying -v or -verbose without other options.

HELP MESSAGES FOR OCLUMON
9200, 3, "For help from command line: oclumon <verb> -h\nFor help in interactive mode: <verb> -h\nCurrently supported verbs are:\nshowtrail, showobjects, dumpnodeview, manage, version, debug, quit, exit, and help\n"

data.message: For help from command line: oclumon <verb> -h\\nFor help in interactive mode: <verb> -h\\nCurrently supported verbs are:\\nshowobjects, dumpnodeview, manage, version, debug, quit, exit, and help\\n
For help from command line: oclumon <verb> -h\\nFor help in interactive mode: <verb> -h\\nCurrently supported verbs are:\\ndumpnodeview, manage, version, set, debug, quit, exit, and help\\n

\\nmanage verb usage\\n=================\\n  manage [[-repos {resize <time>|changesize <memsize>|reploc <new_loc> [[-maxtime <time>]|\\n         [-maxspace <memsize>]] }]|[-get <key1> <key2>..]|\\n[-enable diagsnap] |[-disable diagsnap]\\n\\n*Where\\n
\N

-repos       = Required to specify Cluster Health Monitor repository related options\\n  -get         = Fetch manage information for one or more named keys\\n  <key1> <key2>= <key> can be repsize, reppath, master and replica\\n  resize       = Option for resizing Cluster Health Monitor repository\\n  <time>       = Size of Cluster Health Monitor repository in number of seconds\\n
must be more than %d (1 hour) and less than %d (%d days)\\n
changesize   = Option for Change Cluster Health Monitor repository space limit\\n  <memsize>    = Size of Cluster Health Monitor repository in megabytes\\n

reploc       = Option for Change Repository Location\\n  <new_loc>    = Path to new directory e.g.: /opt/db\\n  -maxtime     = Option to specify Cluster Health Monitor repository size in terms of elapsed seconds of data capture for new location\\n  -maxspace    = Option to specify space limit for new Cluster Health Monitor repository location\\n -enable diagsnap     = Option to enable diagsnap  -disable diagsnap     = Option to disable diagsnap\\n\\n

\\ndebug, set, and get verb usage\\n================\\nset log <daemon> <module:level> = set log level. same as debug log command.\\nget log <daemon> <module> = get current log level\\ndebug {log <daemon> <module:level> | version}\\n\\n*Where\\n  log            = To change log levels\\n  <daemon>       = Daemon whose log level has to be changed\\n                   Following daemons are supported :\\n
osysmond, ologgerd, client, all\\n
osysmond, ologgerd, client, all\\n

<module:level> = Module and level pair\\n                   Supported osysmond modules:\\n                   CRFMOND, CRFM, allcomp, etc.\\n                   Supported ologgerd modules:\\n                   CRFLOGD, CRFLDREP, CRFM, allcomp, etc.\\n                   Supported client modules:\\n                   OCLUMON, CRFM, allcomp, etc.\\n
Supported oproxyd modules:\\n                   CRFPROXY, allcomp\\n

Supported log levels:\\n                   0, 1, 2, 3\\n  version        = To display versions\\n\\n*Note\\n  modules supported for 'all' daemons: allcomp\\n  All daemons support: CRFM, allcomp\\n  See all modules in a daemon by calling oclumon get log <daemon> allcomp\\n  Module name is case-sensitive.\\n\\n*Example:\\n  oclumon debug log osysmond CRFMOND:3\\n  oclumon set log ologgerd CRFLOGD:2\\n  oclumon get log all allcomp\\n

\\ndumpnodeview verb usage\\n=======================\\nThe dumpnodeview command reports monitored records in the text format. The\\ncollection of metrics for a node at a given point in time (a timestamp) is\\ncalled a node view.\\n\\n* Usage\\n

dumpnodeview [-allnodes | -n <node1> ...] [-last <duration> |\\n                -s <timestamp> -e <timestamp>][-i <interval>][-v]\\n                [-system][-process][-device][-filesystem][-nic]\\n                [-protoerr][-cpu][-topconsumer][-format <format type>]\\n                [-dir <directory> [-append]]\\n\\n

*Where\\n  -n <node1> ...   = Dump node views for specified nodes\\n  -allnodes        = Dump node views for all nodes\\n  -s <timestamp>   = Specify start time for range dump of node views\\n  -e <timestamp>   = Specify end time for range dump of node views\\n

Absolute timestamp must be in \\"YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS\\"\\n                     format, for example \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\"\\n  -last <duration> = Dump the latest node views for a specified duration.\\n
Duration must be in \\"HH24:MI:SS\\" format, for example\\n                     \\"00:45:00\\"\\n
-i               = Dump node views separated by the specified\\n                     interval in seconds. Must be a multiple of 5.\\n

-v               = Dump verbose node views containing all parts.\\n  -system, -cpu,.. = Dump each indicate node view parts.\\n  -format <format type> = format of the output.\\n                     <format type> can be legacy, tabular, or csv.\\n                     The default format is mostly tabular with legacy for\\n                      nodeview parts with only one row.\\n  -dir <directory> = Dump node view part to file(s) in spceified dir.\\n                     With -append, will append the

files. Overwrite otherwise.\\n\\n *Requirements and notes\\n  To stop continuous display, use Ctrl-C on Linux or UNIX and Esc on Windows.\\n  -s and -e need to be specified together for range dumps of node views.\\n  The local System Monitor Service (osysmond) must be running to get dumps.\\n
The Cluster Logger Service (ologgerd) must be running to get dumps.\\n  For screen reader user, please use option -format legacy.\\n\\n

*Defaults :\\n  Mode      : Continuous mode\\n\\n*Example :\\n  oclumon dumpnodeview -n node1 node2 node3 -last \\"12:00:00\\"\\n  oclumon dumpnodeview -last \\"00:10:00\\" -i 30\\n  oclumon dumpnodeview -format csv -system -cpu -topconsumer\\n

\\nSHOWTRAIL verb usage\\n====================\\n  showtrail [-n <node>] [[-diskid <diskid> <discparam>]|\\n            [-nicid <nicid> <nicparam>]|[-pid <pid> <procparams>]|\\n            [-sys <systemparam>]]\\n
[-c <regions>][-s <time> -e <time>]|[-last <time1>] [-h]\\n\\n*Where\\n
-n           = show trail for specified node\\n  <node>       = node name for which trail needs to be shown\\n  -s           = To specify time for the start of range queries\\n

-e           = To specify time for the end of range queries\\n  <time>       = Absolute time to be specified within quotes in\\n                 \\"YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS\\" format, like \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\"\\n
IP Protocol Problem

-last        = To specify time for last queries\\n  <time1>      = Time in \\"HH24:MI:SS\\" format to be specified with -last option,like  \\"00:45:00\\"\\n  -diskid      = To request trail of disk parameters\\n

-pid         = To request trail of process parameters\\n  -nicid       = To request trail of NIC parameters\\n  -sys         = To request trail of system-wide parameters\\n  <diskid>     = Disk name whose parameter's trail is required\\n

<nicid>      = NIC ID whose parameters's trail is required\\n  <pid>        = Process id whose parameter's trail is required\\n  <discparams> = Disk parameter whose trail is required\\n                 Following disk parameters are available:\\n                 qlen, totalwaittime\\n
<nicparams>  = NIC parameter whose trail is required\\n                 Following NIC parameters are available:\\n                 effectivebw , errors\\n
<procparams> = Process parameters whose trail is required\\n                 Following process parameters are available:\\n                 cputimepc, memusage, shmem, ioops,thcount, and fdcount\\n

<sysparams>  = System  parameters whose trail is required\\n                 Following system parameters are available:\\n                 usagepc, cpuqlen, cpunumprocess, openfds, numrt,\\n                 numofiosps, memfree,  numofthreads, and iowaitpc\\n

-c           = To request particular regions of interest\\n  <regions>    = List of regions of interest\\n                 Following regions are available\\n                 red,green,yellow,and orange\\n\\n

*Requirements\\n  -s and -e need to be specified together for range queries\\n  The local System Monitor Service should be running to get trail.\\n  The Cluster Logger Service should be running to get trail.\\n\\n*Defaults :\\n  Region    : ALL\\n  Time      : Last 30 min\\n\\n
*Example :\\n  showtrail -n stadn59 -diskid hda1 qlen totalwaittime -s \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\" -e \\"2007-11-12 23:15:00 \\" -c \\"red\\" \\"yellow\\"\\n
\\nshowgaps verb usage\\n====================\\n  showgaps -n <node> [[-s <time> -e <time>]|  [-last <time1>]]\\n           [-t <gapsize>] [-h]\\n\\n*Where\\n
\N

-n        = showgaps for specified node\\n  <node>    = node name for which gaps need to be shown\\n  -s        = To specify time for the start of range queries\\n  -e        = To specify time for the end of range queries\\n

<time>    = Absolute time to be specified within quotes in\\n              \\"YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS\\" format, like \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\"\\n  -last     = To specify time for last queries\\n  <time1>   = Time in \\"HH24:MI:SS\\" format to be specified with -last option,like \\"00:45:00\\"\\n
-t        = To specify minimum threshold for a gap\\n  <gapsize> = Gap size in seconds \\n\\n

*Requirements\\n  -s and -e need to be specified together for range queries\\n  The local System Monitor Service should be running to get gaps.\\n  The Cluster Logger Service should be running to get gaps.\\n\\n*Defaults :\\n  Threshold: 3 (least size of gap)\\n  Time: Last 30 min\\n\\n
\\nshowobjects verb usage\\n======================\\nshowobjects [[-allnodes]|[-n <node> [[-disk]|[-proc]|[-nic]]]][-time <time> [-b <band>]]\\n\\n*Where\\n
\N

-n           = Show objects for specified node\\n  <node>       = Node name for which objects need to be shown\\n  -time        = Time at which objects are required\\n  <time>       = Absolute time to be specified within quotes in\\n                 \\"YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS\\" format, like \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\"\\n  -disk

= To request list of disks\\n  -nic         = To request list of network interface cards\\n  -proc        = To request list of processes\\n  -allnodes    = Shows all the nodes which can be queried\\n  -b           = For specifying maximum look up around <time> in seconds\\n  <band>       = Size of band in seconds\\n\\n

*Requirements\\n  Local System Monitor Service should be running to get objects.\\n  Master loggerd should be running to get objects.\\n\\n*Defaults :\\n  Time    : Current\\n  Option  : -allnodes\\n\\n*Example :\\n  showobjects -n stadn59 -disk -time \\"2008-02-20 02:01:48\\"\\n
\\nanalyze verb usage\\n=======================\\nThe analyze command reports problems pertaining to Oracle Clusterware, ASM and Database.\\n\\n
*Usage\\nanalyze [-allnodes|-n <node1> ...] [-s <time> -e <time>|-last <duration>]\\n        [-r <severity>] [-y <component> ...] [-x <instance name>] [-v]\\n\\n
*Where\\n  -n <node1> ...     = To limit the display to problems associated with the specified nodes\\n
-allnodes          = To analyze problems for all nodes\\n  -s                 = To specify time for the start of range queries\\n  -e                 = To specify time for the end of range queries\\n

<time>             = Absolute time to be specified within quotes in\\n                       \\"YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS\\" format, like \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\n  -last              = To specify relative duration from current time\\n  <duration>         = Duration must be in \\"HH24:MI:SS\\" format, like \\"00:45:00\\"\\n
-r                 = To limit the display to a subset of problems based on severity\\n                       The severity can be HIGH, MEDIUM or LOW\\n
-b                 = To specify a directory containing user models, and override the default models\\n
-d                 = To specify a directory containing data for analysis\\n                       If a component is specified, it must be ASM, DATABASE or both\\n
-y <component> ... = To limit the display to a subset of problems based on component\\n                       The component can be CLUSTERWARE or DATABASE\\n
-x                 = To limit the display to problems associated with a specific database instance\\n                       The component specified must be DATABASE\\n
-v                 = To display results in a verbose format\\n
\\n\\n*Requirements and notes\\n  To stop the display, use Ctrl-C on Linux and Esc on Windows\\n  The -s and -e options need to be specified together for range queries\\n
Analysis for the last 30 minutes is displayed when no time or duration is specified  \\n  The Grid Infrastructure Management Repository must be active to complete the analysis\\n\\n
The Cluster Logger Service aborted on host %s. Details at %s in %s.
data.cause: The Cluster Logger Service aborted due to an internal\nerror.
data.action: If the problem persists, run 'diagcollection.pl' and contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: *Example:\\n  oclumon analyze -n stadn59 -s \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\" -e \\"2007-11-12 23:35:00\\" -y CLUSTERWARE\\n  oclumon analyze -n stadn19 -s \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\" -e \\"2007-11-12 23:35:00\\" -y DATABASE -x storedb3\\n  oclumon analyze -allnodes -s \\"2007-11-12 23:05:00\\" -e \\"2007-11-12 23:35:00\\" -y CLUSTERWARE\\n
\\ncalibrate verb usage\\n=======================\\nThe calibrate command calibrates the models pertaining to Oracle Clusterware, ASM and Database.\\n\\n

*Usage\\ncalibrate {-s <time> -e <time>}\\n          -y <component>\\n          {-allnodes|-n <host>|-o <serverpool name>|{-w <database name> [-o <serverpool name>]}}\\n          [-q <model name>] [-v]\\n\\n
*Where\\n  -s                 = To specify the start time of the data used for model calibration\\n  -e                 = To specify the end time of the data used for model calibration\\n
<time>             = Absolute time to be specified within quotes in\\n                       \\"YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS\\" format, like \\"2012-11-12 23:05:00\\"\\n
-y <component>     = To calibrate a specific model based on the component\\n                       The component can be CLUSTERWARE, ASM or DATABASE.\\n
-allnodes          = Calibrate models for all nodes\\n                       The component specified must be CLUSTERWARE.\\n
-n <host>          = To limit the model calibration to a specific host\\n                       The component specified must be CLUSTERWARE.\\n
-w <database name> = To limit the model calibration to a specific database\\n                       The component specified must be DATABASE.\\n
-o <serverpool name> = To limit the model calibration to a specific server pool in a policy-managed cluster\\n
-v                 = To display results in a verbose format\\n

-q <model name>    = Optional model provided by user.\\n                       If a model is not provided, the current model is calibrated.\\n                       If a model is provided, then an existing model is calibrated if one exists.\\n                       If a model is provided, and it does not exist, then an existing model is cloned, and the cloned model is calibrated.\\n
\\n*Requirements and notes\\n  To stop the display, use Ctrl-C on Linux and Esc on Windows.\\n  The -s and -e options need to be specified together for range queries.\\n
The Grid Infrastructure Management Repository must be active to complete the calibration.\\n
An instance of the database must be active on the node the command is issued when the DATABASE component is specified.
The instance whose model will be calibrated may be remote and does not have to be active.\\n
The target i.e. database or host will not be monitored while the model is being calibrated.\\n
The command must be issued by a privileged user.\\n\\n
*Example :\\n  oclumon calibrate -s \\"2012-11-12 09:05:00\\" -e \\"2012-11-12 11:05:00\\" -y CLUSTERWARE -n stadn59\\n

oclumon calibrate -s \\"2012-11-12 10:05:00\\" -e \\"2012-11-12 12:35:00\\" -y DATABASE -w storedb\\n  oclumon calibrate -s \\"2012-11-12 22:05:00\\" -e \\"2012-11-12 23:35:00\\" -y DATABASE -w storedb -o SERVERPOOLBIG -q BACKUP\\n

\\nManage verb usage\\n=================\\n  manage -repos {checkretentiontime <time> | changerepossize <memsize>} |\\n\\t -get {<key1> [<key2> ...] | alllogger [-details] | mylogger [-details]} |\\n\\t -enable {diagsnap} | -disable {diagsnap} \\n\\n*Where\\n
\N

-repos\\t\\t= Required to specify Cluster Health Monitor repository related options\\n  -get\\t\\t\\t= Fetch manage information for one or more named keys\\n  <key1> <key2>\\t\\t= <key> can be repsize, reppath, master, mylogger and alllogger \\n  alllogger\\t\\t= Special key with -get to get list of all nodes running Cluster Logger Service

\\n  mylogger\\t\\t= Special key with -get to get the node running the Cluster Logger Service which is serving the current node\\n  -details\\t\\t= Option with alllogger and mylogger for listing nodes served by the Cluster Logger Service\\n  checkretentiontime    = Option to confirm whether specified time retention can be realized for current Cluster Health Monitor repository size
\\n  <time>\\t\\t= Retention of Cluster Health Monitor repository in number of seconds\\n
changerepossize\\t= Option for Change Cluster Health Monitor repository space limit\\n  <memsize>\\t\\t= Size of Cluster Health Monitor repository in megabytes\\n

-csvlog\\t\\t= Options related to comma separated value output from Cluster Health Monitor\\n  status\\t\\t= Comma separated values feature status: ON or OFF.  Feature is ON by default.\\n  interval <time>\\t= Option to specify comma separated values sampling interval in whole clock seconds. Default sampling interval is 60 seconds.\\n
logduration <size>\\t= Option to specify comma separated values data file boundary in megabytes. Default file boundary is 10 megabytes.\\n\\n

*Requirements\\n  The local cluster synchronization service must be running to change the retention time of the Cluster Health Monitor repository.\\n  The Cluster Logger Service must be running to change the retention time of the Cluster Health Monitor repository.\\n\\n*Example :\\n
manage -get MASTER \\n  manage -repos checkretentiontime 86400\\n  manage -repos changerepossize 6000\\n  manage -get alllogger -details\\n  manage -enable diagsnap \\n\\n
manage -csvlog status off\\n  manage -csvlog interval 50\\n  manage -csvlog logduration 300\\n
-enable diagsnap\\t= Option to enable diagsnap script\\n  -disable diagsnap\\t= Option to disable diagsnap script\\n

data.message: Internal error in credentials processing.
data.cause: An unexpected condition was detected in the credentials module.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: Failed to allocate process memory.
data.cause: There were insufficient system memory resources.
data.action: Correct the system memory resources problem and retry. If this does not appear to be caused by an operating system issue, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.cause: An attempt to communicate with Oracle Cluster Registry (OCR) or Oracle Local Registry (OLR) credential storage failed.
data.action: Run the 'crsctl check crs' command to determine whether Cluster Ready Services or Oracle High Availability Services are online.

data.message: Credential domain already exists.

data.action: Specify another credential domain path.

data.message: Credential set already exists.
data.cause: The provided credential set already existed.
data.action: Specify another credential domain path to which the credential set will be added.

data.message: Credential target already exists.
data.cause: The provided credential target already existed.
data.action: Specify another credential target name, or modify the value of the existing one.

data.message: Credential set member does not exist.
data.cause: The provided credential set member did not exist.
data.action: Specify another credential set member or create a new member.

data.action: Specify another credential set or create a new member.

data.action: Depending on the reason, this operation may be retried after correcting the situation.

data.message: Invalid argument specified for attribute.
data.cause: An invalid argument was found for a given attribute.
data.action: Rerun the command using correct value.

data.message: User name or group name does not match the owner or group of the credential object.
data.cause: Credential permissions for the owner could not be modified because the user name did not match the owner of the credential.
data.action: Specify the owner's user ID in the argument to change owner's permission.

data.message: ACL string is missing the user or group modifier.
data.cause: The access control list (ACL) string did not specify whether user's or group's permission needs to be changed.
data.action: Specify the correct format in the argument and rerun the command.

data.message: Credentials target does not exist.
data.cause: The provided credentials target did not exist.
data.action: Specify another credentials target.

data.message: The directory '%s' does not exist.
data.cause: The specified directory did not exist.
data.action: Provide a directory for which the user has read and write permissions.

data.message: The directory '%s' is not accessible.
data.cause: An attempt to access the specified directory failed.
data.action: Ensure that the user has read and write permissions on the directory.

data.message: Unable to open file '%s' for read access.
data.cause: An attempt to open the specified file for read access failed.
data.action: Ensure that the user has read access permission on the file.

data.message: Unable to open file '%s' for write access.
data.cause: An attempt to open the specified file for write access failed.
data.action: Ensure that the user has write access permission on the file.

data.message: Section name does not exist.
data.cause: The credentials could not be imported because the provided section name did not exist in the XML file.
data.action: Verify the sections included in the credentials file and retry the import supplying the correct section name.

data.message: Credential set of type '%s' does not support the specified attribute '%s'.
data.cause: An attempted operation on a credential set of the indicated type was rejected because it specified an attribute that was not valid for credential sets of that type.
data.action: Retry the operation specifying an attribute supported for the set.

data.message: Credential file specified is either empty or corrupt.
data.cause: Credential import failed because the import file was empty or\ncorrupt.
data.action: Specify a valid credential file and try again.

data.message: failed to delete site '%s' because it was the last remaining site
data.cause: An attempt to delete the indicated site was rejected because it was\nthe last remaining site.
data.action:
Execute the command 'crsctl query cluster site -all' to list the
the existing sites. Refer to the command inline help or product
documentation for more information.

data.message: invalid site name '%s' specified
data.cause: The indicated string was provided where a site name was required,\nbut it was not a valid site name.
data.action:
Specify a site name which is at least one character long but no more
than 15 characters in length. A site name consists of alphanumeric
characters and the hyphen character (a..z,A..Z,0..9,-). It cannot
begin or end with the hyphen (-) character.

data.message: The configured site name '%s' is invalid.
data.cause: A failure occurred while retrieving site information. The\nconfigured site name was invalid.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: The number of sites defined is more than the maximum.
data.cause: A failure occurred while retrieving site information. There were\nmore sites defined than the maximum allowed.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: The site GUID '%s' configured for site '%s' is invalid.
data.cause: A failure occurred while retrieving site information. The\nconfigured site Globally Unique Identifier (GUID) was\nsyntactically invalid.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: Host '%s' not assigned to a site.
data.cause: A failure occurred while retrieving the site assignment for the\nindicated host. The host has not been assigned to any site.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: The site '%s' does not exist.
The site '%s' already exists.
The site GUID '%s' configured for host '%s' is invalid.
data.cause: A failure occurred while retrieving the site information for the\nindicated host. The site GUID configured for the indicated host\nwas invalid.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.\n

data.message: failed to add site '%s' because the number of sites cannot exceed %d
data.cause: The maximum number of sites were already defined.
data.action:
To add the indicated site name, execute the command
'crsctl query cluster site -all' to list the existing sites, delete
an existing site using the command 'crsctl delete cluster site',
and retry the original command. Refer to the command inline help or
product documentation for more information.

data.message: invalid site GUID '%s' specified
data.cause: An attempt to add a site required for an Exadata Cell was rejected\nbecause the supplied Globally Unique Identifier (GUID) was\nsyntactically invalid.
data.action:
Retry the command specifying the Globally Unique Identifier (GUID)
as a text string of 16 hexadecimal digits (0-f) without a hyphen (-)
character or the hexadecimal literal prefix (0x). Refer to the
command inline help or product documentation for more information.

data.message: failed to add site '%s' because specified GUID '%s' is already configured
failed to add site '%s' because the number of sites cannot exceed %s
data.cause: An attempt to add the indicated site was rejected because the\nmaximum allowed number of sites had already been defined.
data.action:
To add the indicated site name, execute the command
'crsctl query cluster site -all' to list the existing sites, delete
an existing site using the command 'crsctl delete cluster site',
and retry the original command. Refer to the command inline help or
product documentation for more information.

data.cause: The Oracle Virtual Machine (Oracle VM) user name and password combination did not work, or the user did not have permission to perform the action requested.

data.cause: A connection to the Oracle Virtual Machine (Oracle VM) Manager could not be established or timed out.

data.action: Create or modify the credentials by using the 'srvctl {add | modify} ovmm' command.

data.cause: An attempt was made to operate on a resource group that is not\nregistered.
data.action: Ensure that the resource group name is specified correctly using the command 'crsctl status resourcegroup'.

data.message: cannot stop resource group '%s' because it is not running
data.cause: A request to stop a resource group that is not running was received.
data.action: Check the current state of the resource group; it should no\nlonger be running.

data.message: Resource group '%s' is disabled.
data.cause: The resource group is currently disabled and so may not be operated on.
data.action: Enable the resource group and re-submit your request.

data.message: Resource group '%s' is in UNKNOWN state and must be stopped first.
data.cause: An attempt to start a resource group failed because the group state was UNKNOWN.
data.action: Stop the resource group manually, make sure it is OFFLINE, and then\nre-submit the request.

data.message: cannot start resource group '%(1)s' because no online server satisfies its placement policy
data.cause: An attempt to start the indicated resource group failed\nbecause no online server satisfies the constraints imposed by its\nplacement policy.
data.action: Reissue the command after modifying the placement policy for the\nresource group or adding appropriate servers to the cluster.

data.cause: An attempt to configure the dependencies of a resource group was rejected because the\nindicated resource group type does not exist.
data.action: Reissue the command specifying a valid resource group type.

data.cause: An attempt to configure the dependencies of a resource group failed because of\nerrors in the dependency specification.
data.action: Check the accompanying error messages and reissue the command after correcting the\ndependency specification.

data.cause: An attempt to configure the dependencies of a resource group resulted in a\ncircular dependency and was rejected.
data.action: Reissue the command after correcting the cause of the circular dependency.

data.cause: The resource group profile does not have a server pool specified.
data.action: Specify an existing server pool in the profile and re-submit the request.

data.cause: A required attribute is missing from the resource group profile.
data.action: Add the attribute to the profile and resubmit the request.

data.cause: All instances of the resource group are running and the start\nrequest did not have the -force option specified.
data.action: Either specify the -force option or re-evaluate the need for the\nrequest.

data.action: This message will usually be coupled with another one that details\nthe nature of the problem with the other resource group. Follow up\non the action recommended for that message.

data.cause: A resource group with specified name was already registered.
data.action: Use a unique name for the new resource group.

data.message: illegal attempt to update internal or read-only attribute '%(1)s' for resource group '%(2)s'
data.cause: An internal or read-only attribute of the resource group was specified in the update resource group request.
data.action: Exclude internal and read-only attributes from your request.

data.message: cannot relocate local resource group '%(1)s'
data.cause: An attempt to relocate the indicated resource group failed because\nresource groups of type local cannot relocate to another server.
data.action: Reissue the command specifying only relocatable resource groups.

data.message: Resource group '%s' cannot be restored to its original state after a failed relocate attempt.
data.cause: After an unsuccessful attempt to relocate a resource group, CRSD was unable to restore the resource group.
data.action: Manual intervention may be required. Re-try starting the resource group.

data.message: Resource group type '%s' cannot be unregistered because there are types that are based on it.
data.cause: An attempt was made to unregister a resource group type that has other types inherited from it.
data.action: Remove inherited types first, then remove this one.

data.message: Resource group type '%(1)s' cannot be unregistered because it has the following resource groups: %(2)s
data.cause: An attempt was made to unregister a resource group type when resource groups based on that type exist.
data.action: Remove the specified resource groups first, then remove the type.

data.message: Resource group type '%s' does not exist.
data.cause: An attempt was made to unregister a resource group type that does not exist.
data.action: Specify a registered resource group type.

data.message: Resource group type '%(1)s' cannot be unregistered because it is referenced by resource group '%(2)s'.
data.cause: An attempt was made to unregister a resource group type when other resource groups are dependent on the type.
data.action: Make sure there are no existing resource groups that reference this type in their dependencies.

data.message: Resource group '%(1)s' cannot be relocated because it is not running.
data.cause: An attempt to relocate the resource group failed because it was not running.
data.action: Ensure that the resource group is running before issuing the request.

data.message: Failed to relocate resource group '%(1)s'. Will attempt to restore it on '%(2)s' now.
data.cause: Relocate of a resource group failed on all possible servers and\nis now being restarted on original server.
data.action: None, this is an informational message.

data.message: Attempt to relocate resource group '%(1)s' to '%(2)s' has failed. Will re-retry on '%(3)s' now.
data.cause: Relocate of a resource group has failed for the server; a retry\nis in progress.
data.action: None, this is an informational message.

data.message: Base resource group type '%s' does not exist.
data.cause: An attempt was made to register a resource group type with an unknown base type.
data.action: Use an existing type as a base. Run 'crsctl status resourcegrouptype' to list registered resource group types.

data.message: Dependency type '%(1)s' is specified more than once for resource group '%(2)s'.
data.cause: An attempt to configure the dependencies of a resource group was rejected\nbecause a dependency type was used more than once in the profile of the resource group.
data.action: Reissue the command after combining multiple specifications of the same\ndependency type into a single clause.

data.message: cannot unregister built-in resource group type
data.cause: An attempt was made to delete a built-in resource group type.
data.action: Specify a resource group type that is not built-in.

data.message: cannot specify attribute '%s' on a per-server basis
data.cause: An attempt was made to register or update a resource group with an invalid per-server attribute.
data.action: Check the permitted per-server attributes for the resource group, fix and resubmit. Run 'crsctl status resourcegroup' to check the attributes of the resource group.

data.message: could not find resource group '%s'
data.cause: An attempt was made to operate on a resource group that is not\nregistered.
data.action: Check if the resource group is registered. Run 'crsctl status resourcegroup' to list all registered resource groups.

data.message: The owner of resource group '%(1)s' does not have execute permission on pool '%(2)s'.
data.cause: An attempt to start a resource group referenced a server pool on which the\nowner of the resource group lacks execute permission.
data.action: Either have the pool's permission changed appropriately or\nuse a different pool.

data.message: There are no more servers to attempt to place resource group '%(1)s' that would satisfy its placement policy.
data.cause: An operation to start, relocate or failover the indicated resource\ngroup failed after attempts were made on all available servers.
data.action: Reissue the command after rectifying the failure condition.

data.message: Required resource group '%s' is missing.
data.cause: A resource group that's configured as required is not registered.
data.action: Register the missing resource group or update the dependency\nspecification so as to the missing resource group is not required for\nstart.

data.message: The server pools where resource group '%s' could run have no servers.
data.cause: An attempt to start a resource group failed because all the configured\nserver pools have no servers assigned.
data.action: Either make sure there are active servers in the pools or\nuse different pools for the resource group.

data.message: No hosting members of resource group '%s' are online or are allowed to be used by the resource group.
data.cause: An attempt to start a resource group failed because no server specified as\nhosting member is online or, if it is, may be used by the resource group.
data.action: Either add more servers to the cluster or request permission to pools to\nwhich currently available servers are assigned.

data.message: cannot create resource groups of abstract type '%s'
data.cause: An attempt to create a resource group specified an abstract resource group type.
data.action: Specify a concrete resource group type for the resource group.

data.message: Resource Group '%(1)s' with %(2)s=%(3)s may only run on servers assigned to pools %(4)s and %(5)s, both of which are empty.
data.cause: An attempt to start a resource group failed because it's  placement policy only allows\nit to run on servers assigned to the specified pools, and they are all empty.
data.action: Either change the placement policy of the resource group, or\nchange the cluster configuration so that there are servers in those\npools.

data.message: Attempting to start resource group '%(1)s' on server '%(2)s'
data.cause: This is a status message.
data.action: None.

data.message: Attempting to stop resource group '%(1)s' on server '%(2)s'
data.cause: This is a status message.
data.action: None.

data.message: Start of resource group '%(1)s' on server '%(2)s' failed.
data.cause: This is a status message.
data.action: None.

data.message: Stop of resource group '%(1)s' on server '%(2)s' failed.
data.cause: This is a status message.
data.action: None.

data.message: Start of resource group '%(1)s' on server '%(2)s' succeeded.
data.cause: This is a status message.
data.action: None.

data.message: Stop of resource group '%(1)s' on server '%(2)s' succeeded.
data.cause: This is a status message.
data.action: None.

data.message: Server '%(1)s' is not in any of the server pools hosting resource group '%(2)s'.
data.cause: An attempt was made to start a resource group on a server that is\nnot currently an active server in any of the resource group's server pools.
data.action: Use a server name that is currently an active server of the\nresource group's server pools.

data.message: Server '%(1)s' is not a hosting member of resource group '%(2)s'.
data.cause: An attempt was made to start the resource group on a server not\nlisted as a hosting member of the resource group.
data.action: Use a server name that is listed as a hosting member.

data.message: Resource group '%(1)s' cannot be started on server '%(2)s' because the server is not in either '%(3)s' or '%(4)s' server pools.
data.cause: The resource group's placement policy only allows it to run in\nthe specified server pools. An attempt was made to start it on a server\nassigned to a different pool.
data.action: Either use a different server or set the value of\nSERVER_POOLS to *, which will allow the resource to run on any server.

data.message: The instance of resource group '%(1)s' can only run on server '%(2)s'; check on server '%(3)s' is unnecessary.
data.cause: A check was issued on a server for a resource group instance that can only\nrun on a particular server.
data.action: Issue a check on the server where the resource group instance is\nsupposed to be run.

data.message: No instance of resource group '%(1)s' found on server '%(2)s'.
data.cause: A check command failed because the resource group was not running on the specified server\nand no offline instances were available for the resource group.
data.action: Reissue the command, specifying a server where a resource group instance\nmight be running.

data.message: A resource group type with the name '%s' is already registered.
data.cause: An attempt to register a resource group type specified a name that is already registered.
data.action: Use a unique name for the new resource group type.

data.message: Attribute '%s' cannot be overridden for a resource group type.
data.cause: An attribute was specified that is not allowed in a resource group type.
data.action: Do not specify the indicated attribute for a resource group type.

data.message: Resource group '%s' depends on resource group '%s'.
data.cause: An attempt to unregister a resource group failed because another resource\ngroup is dependent on it.
data.action: Reissue the command after removing all dependencies on the resource group to\nbe unregistered.

data.message: The resource group '%(1)s' is already running on target server '%(2)s'.
data.cause: An attempt to relocate the indicated resource group failed because\nthe resource group was already running on the indicated server.
data.action: No action is required.

data.message: cannot proceed with command because it requires stopping resource group '%(1)s' on server '%(2)s'
data.cause: The command failed because the force option was not specified to\nstop the indicated resource groups.
data.action: Reissue the command after adding more servers to the cluster or\nspecify the force option.

data.message: Failed to delete resource group type '%(1)s' from repository. Details at %(2)s in %(3)s.
data.cause: An attempt to delete a resource group type encountered an internal error while updating the repository.
data.action: Use the ocrcheck utility to detect errors in OCR. If problems exist, the registry may need to be recovered or restored.

data.message: cannot stop resource group '%(1)s' because it is not running on server '%(2)s'
data.cause: An request to stop a resource group on a server where it is not\nrunning was received.
data.action: Check the current state of the resource group; it should no\nlonger be running on that server.

data.message: No instance of resource group '%s' should be running.
data.cause: An attempt to relocate a resource group was rejected  because the TARGET attributes of the instances of the resource group were set to OFFLINE.
data.action: Restart the resource group to change the value of the TARGET attribute to ONLINE.

data.message: cannot start resource group '%(1)s' because it has a '%(2)s' dependency on resource group type '%(3)s' and no resource group of that type can satisfy the dependency
data.cause: An attempt to start the indicated resource group failed because a\nresource group of the indicated type did not exist to satisfy the dependency.
data.action: Reissue the command after registering a resource group of the indicated type.

data.message: failed to stop resource group while attempting CARDINALITY modification
data.cause: An attempt to stop a resource group during CARDINALITY modification failed.
data.action: Use 'crsctl stop resourcegroup' to stop the resource group manually and then retry the update operation.

data.message: Resource group '%(1)s' cannot start on server '%(2)s' because the server does not belong to the resource group's server category.
data.cause: An attempt to start the resource group group failed because the server specified does not\nbelong to the server category of the resource group.
data.action: Specify a server that belongs to the category.

data.message: There are no servers that belong to the server category '%(1)s' of resource group '%(2)s'.
data.cause: The resource group cannot be started as there are no available servers that belong to its category.
data.action: Add servers to the cluster or change the category to be more inclusive.

data.message: Resource group '%(1)s' is not configured to run in server pool '%(2)s'.
data.cause: An attempt was made to start or stop the resource group in a server pool where the resource group was not configured to run.
data.action: Modify resource group's attribute to have this server pool or specify a different resource group.

data.message: cannot stop resource group '%(1)s' because it is not running in server pool '%(2)s'
data.cause: A resource group stop request specified a server pool on which the resource group is not running.
data.action: Check the current state of the resource group; it should no\nlonger be running in that server pool.

data.message: cannot relocate resource group '%(1)s' because it is not a singleton resource group
data.cause: A relocate resource group request specified a resource group that\nhas multiple instances.
data.action: Reissue the request specifying a singleton resource group or\nuse a filter that resolves to an instance of the group.

data.message: Resource group '%s' has no instances to act upon.
data.cause: An attempt was made to act on a resource group that has no\ninstances because it is configured to run on servers that\nhave never existed in the cluster.
data.action: Retry the command when the resource group has instances.

data.message: cannot add resource group '%s' because a resource exists with the same name
data.cause: An attempt to add a resource group failed because a resource with\nthe same name was already registered.
data.action: Reissue the command specifying a different name for the new resource group.

rgName          Modify named resourcegroup\\n     attrName        Attribute name\\n     value           Attribute value\\n     server          Server name\\n     cid             Resource group cardinality ID\\n     -f              Force option\\n     -delete         Delete named attribute\\n     -i              Fail if request cannot be processed immediately

\\n     -s               Server pool names (e.g. -s  pool1 pool2)\\n

-l               Leave affected resource groups as-is if request fails\\n     -s               Server pool names (e.g. -s  pool1 pool2)\\n

cannot delete the resource group because it does not exist
data.cause: An attempt to delete a resource group failed because the resource group specification did not identify an existing resource group. Either there was no resource group with the specified name, or no resource group satisfied the specified filter.
data.action: Reissue the command specifying the name of an existing resource group or a filter that will select an existing resource group.

data.message: cannot delete the resource group type because it does not exist
data.cause: An attempt to delete a resource group type failed because the resource group type specification did not identify an existing resource group type. Either there was no resource group type with the specified name, or no resource group type satisfied the specified filter.
data.action: Reissue the command specifying the name of an existing resource group type or a filter that will select an existing resource group type.

data.message: Restored the state of resource group '%(1)s' on server '%(2)s'
data.cause: This is a status message.
data.action: None.

data.message: Resource '%(1)s' is already a member of resource group '%(2)s'.
data.cause: An attempt was made to add a resource to a group while the resource was already a member of another group.
data.action: Reissue the command after removing the resource from its current group.

data.message: cannot add local resource '%(1)s' to cluster resource group '%(2)s'
data.cause: An attempt was made to add a local resource to a cluster resource group. Only cluster resources can be added to a cluster resource group.
data.action: Reissue the command by specifying only cluster resources.

data.message: cannot add cluster resource '%(1)s' to local resource group '%(2)s'
data.cause: An attempt was made to add a cluster resource to a local resource group. Only local resources can be added to a local resource group.
data.action: Reissue the command by specifying only local resources.

data.message: Resource '%(1)s' cannot be added to resource group '%(2)s' because their '%(3)s' attribute values are not identical.
data.cause: An attempt was made to add a resource to a resource group when the resource's profile is not compatible with the group.
data.action: Reissue the command after updating the resource's profile to match the resource group's profile or specify a compatible resource group.

data.message: cannot register resource group '%s' because CRITICAL_RESOURCES attribute is not specified
data.cause: An attempt was made to add a resource group without specifying the critical resources of the group.
data.action: Reissue the command after designating some resource(s) as critical for the group.

data.message: cannot register resource group '%(1)s' because critical resource '%(2)s' is not a member of the group
data.cause: An attempt was made to add or update a resource group and an\ninvalid resource was specified as critical.
data.action: Reissue the command after correcting the CRITICAL_RESOURCES\nattribute of the group or specify the -force option.

data.message: Dependency type '%(1)s' not supported for resource '%(2)s' because it is a member of resource group '%(3)s'
data.cause: A dependency type was specified for a resource that is not supported when a resource is a member of a group.
data.action: Reissue the command, specifying a supported dependency type.

data.message: Resource '%(1)s' cannot have a dependency on resource '%(2)s' because they are not members of the same resource group.
data.cause: An attempt was made to define a dependency between resources who are not members of the same resource group.
data.action: Reissue the command, specifying a target resource that is member of the group.

data.message: cannot modify internal resource group '%s'
data.cause: An attempt was made to modify an internal resource group created by Oracle Clusterware.
data.action: Reissue the command by specifying an appropriate resource group.

data.message: cannot delete internal resource group '%s'
data.cause: An attempt was made to delete an internal resource group created by Oracle Clusterware.
data.action: Reissue the command by specifying an appropriate resource group.

data.message: cannot start resource group '%(1)s' because it is incomplete
data.cause: An attempt to start a resource group failed because it had not been completely populated.
data.action: Check the RESOURCE_LIST and CRITICAL_RESOURCES attributes of the resource group, ensure they are not blank and retry.

data.message: cannot start resource '%(1)s' outside of its resource group '%(2)s'
data.cause: An attempt to start the indicated critical resource of the indicated resource group failed because critical resources cannot be started independently of the group.
data.action: Start the resource group and that will start the critical resources of the group.

data.message: cannot start resource '%(1)s' because its resource group '%(2)s' is not running
data.cause: An attempt to start the indicated resource of the indicated resource group failed because the resource group was not online.
data.action: Start the resource group before attempting to start the resources of the group.

data.message: cannot stop resource '%(1)s' outside of its resource group '%(2)s'
data.cause: An attempt to stop the indicated resource of the indicated resource group failed because it was a critical resource necessary for continuing group operation.
data.action: To stop the indicated resource, stop the entire resource group.

data.message: cannot modify critical resources of a resource group when it is running
data.cause: An attempt was made to modify the CRITICAL_RESOURCES attribute of a resource group when it was running.
data.action: Reissue the command after stopping the resource group on all servers.

data.message: cannot remove critical resource '%(1)s' from resource group '%(2)s'
data.cause: An attempt was made to remove a critical member resource of a resource group.
data.action: Reconsider the removal. If it is necessary, update the CRITICAL_RESOURCES attribute of the group to categorize the resource as not critical, then reissue this command.

data.message: cannot remove resource '%(1)s' from resource group '%(2)s' because another resource in the group '%(3)s' is dependent on it
data.cause: An attempt was made to remove a member resource of a group when other group members were dependent on it.
data.action: Reconsider the removal. If it is necessary, update other resources in the group to remove dependencies on the indicated resource, then reissue the command.

data.message: cannot remove resource '%(1)s' from resource group '%(2)s' because it is dependent on other resources in the group
data.cause: An attempt was made to remove a member resource of a group when it was dependent on other resources in the group.
data.action: Reconsider the removal. If it is necessary, update the indicated resource to remove all dependencies, then reissue the command.

data.message: cannot delete resource '%(1)s' because it is a member of resource group '%(2)s'
data.cause: An attempt was made to delete a resource that was a member of a resource group.
data.action: Reissue the command after removing the resource from the resource group.

data.message: cannot start resource group '%(1)s' because it is in debug mode
data.cause: An attempt to start the resource group failed because the DEBUG attribute was set to 1.
data.action: Reissue the command after setting the DEBUG attribute of the resource group to 0.

data.message: cannot set resource group '%(1)s' to debug mode because it is ONLINE
data.cause: An attempt to update the DEBUG attribute of the resource group failed because it was running.
data.action: Reissue the command after stopping the resource group on all servers.

data.message: cannot clear debug mode of resource group '%(1)s' because some members are ONLINE
data.cause: An attempt to update the DEBUG attribute of the resource group failed because some member resources were running.
data.action: Reissue the command after stopping all member resources of the indicated group.

data.message: Found no resource groups to stop.
Found no resource groups to start.
No resource groups found running on server '%(1)s'.
Resource group '%(1)s' is not running on server '%(2)s'.
data.cause: An attempt to relocate the resource group failed because it was not running on the specified server.
data.action: Ensure that the correct server is specified and reissue the command.

data.message: cannot add resource '%(1)s' to resource group '%(2)s' because the resource is online
data.cause: An attempt to add a resource to a resource group was rejected because the resource was online.
data.action: Reissue the command after stopping the resource on all servers.

data.message: cannot delete resource group '%(1)s' because it has member resources
data.cause: An attempt to delete a resource group failed because because it had member resources.
data.action: Reissue the command after removing all resources from the group.

data.message: User '%(1)s' does not have sufficient permissions to update the resource group '%(2)s'.
data.cause: An attempt to update the resource group of a resource was rejected because the user did not have update privileges on the resource group.
data.action: Reissue the command after update privileges have been granted on the resource group.

data.message: cannot add resource '%(1)s' to resource group '%(2)s' because the resource group owner '%(3)s' cannot operate on the resource
data.cause: An attempt to add a resource to a resource group was rejected because the resource group owner did not have execute privileges on the resource.
data.action: Reissue the command after granting execute privileges on the resource to the resource group owner.

data.message: Resource group '%(1)s' cannot be started because the critical resource '%(2)s' is disabled.
data.cause: An attempt to start the indicated resource group failed because a critical resource was disabled.
data.action: Reissue the command after enabling the indicated critical resource.

data.message: cannot configure attribute '%(1)s' because the resource is a member of a resource group
data.cause: An attempt to update an attribute of a member resource was rejected because that attribute cannot be configured at an individual resource level.
data.action: Reissue the command after removing the indicated attribute.

data.message: Invalid dependency modifier '%(1)s' specified for a group member resource.
data.cause: An attempt to configure the dependencies of a resource was rejected because the indicated modifier was invalid for resources belonging to a group.
data.action: Reissue the command without the indicated modifier in the dependency specification of the resource.

data.message: Resource group '%(1)s' is already running on '%(2)s'.
data.cause: This is a status message.
data.action: None.

data.message: cannot start resource group '%(1)s' because critical resource '%(2)s' is not a member of the group
data.cause: An attempt was made to start a resource group and an invalid\nresource was specified as critical.
data.action: Reissue the command after correcting the CRITICAL_RESOURCES\nattribute of the group.

data.message: No activities match the query.
data.cause: There were no activities found in the cluster activity log that matched the query provided.
data.action: Verify the query parameters and retry.

data.message: Cluster Synchronization Services is unavailable.
data.cause: The requested operation failed because of a failure to communicate with the Cluster Synchronization Services daemon.
data.action: Run the command 'crsctl check css' to determine whether the Cluster Synchronization Services daemon is properly configured and is running.

data.message: authorization wallet not found
data.cause: An attempt to access the cluster activity log failed because the authorization wallet could not be found.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: internal error
data.cause: An unexpected condition was detected in the cluster activity log module.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: unable to allocate process memory
data.cause: The requested operation failed because of a failure to allocate process memory. This was probably due to a lack of system resources.
data.action: Correct the system memory resources problem and retry. If this does not appear to be caused by an operating system issue, contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: unable to connect to the Event Manager daemon
data.cause: The requested operation failed because of a failure to communicate with the Event Manager daemon.
data.action: Run the command 'crsctl check evmd' to determine whether the Event Manager daemon is properly configured and is running.

data.message: insufficient permission for accessing the cluster activity log
data.cause: A non-privileged user attempted to view or modify the cluster activity log.
data.action: Issue the command again as a privileged user.

data.message: invalid filter expression '%s'
data.cause: An attempt to access the cluster activity log failed because the specified filter was invalid.
data.action: Correct the syntax of the filter being provided and try again.

data.message: invalid regular expression '%s'
data.cause: An attempt to access the cluster activity log failed because the specified regular expression was invalid.
data.action: Correct the syntax of the regular expression being provided and try again.

data.message: unable to connect to the Oracle Cluster Registry: %s
data.cause: An attempt to communicate with the Oracle Cluster Registry (OCR) or the Oracle Local Registry (OLR) failed.
data.action: Run the command 'crsctl check crs' to determine whether Cluster Ready Services or Oracle High Availability Services are online.

data.message: Cluster activity log is not supported in this configuration.
data.cause: The Grid Infrastructure Management Repository was not configured.
data.action: Re-Install Grid Infrastructure and ensure that the Grid\nInfrastructure Management Repository is configured.

data.message: cluster activity log maximum size below minimum of 100 MB
data.cause: An attempt to set the maximum size of the cluster activity log specified a value less than the minimum of 100 MB.
data.action: Specify a maximum size of 100 MB or more.

data.message: invalid timestamp '%s'
data.cause: An attempt to access the cluster activity log failed because the specified timestamp was invalid.
data.action: Reissue the command with a valid timestamp. Refer to the command line help for more information.

data.message: invalid duration '%s'
data.cause: An attempt to access the cluster activity log failed because the specified duration was invalid.
data.action: Reissue the command with a valid duration. Refer to the command line help for more information.

data.message: Setting the maximum size for cluster activity log failed.
data.cause: The cluster activity log maximum size could not be modified.
data.action: See the accompanying error message and respond accordingly.

data.message: Setting the retention time for cluster activity log failed.
data.cause: The cluster activity log retention time could not be modified.
data.action: Examine the accompanying error messages and respond accordingly.

data.message: invalid combination of parameters 'timestamp_before', 'timestamp_after' and 'timestamp_duration'
data.cause: The parameters 'timestamp_before', 'timestamp_after' and 'timestamp_duration' were all specified as part of the cluster acitivity log query.
data.action: Retry the cluster activity log query with a valid parameter combination.

data.message: Resize operation for cluster activity log failed because the maximum size or retention time specified was too large. Detailed error: '%s'
data.cause: The value specified for the maximum size or retention time of the cluster activity log was too large and could not be accommodated.
data.action: Specify a lower value for maximum size or retention time.

data.message: The operation will delete all entries in cluster activity log. Rerun with '-f' option.
data.cause: The operation to shrink the cluster activity log was issued without the '-f' option.
data.action: If appropriate, reissue the command with the '-f' option.\n

data.message: crsctl query crs lastactivetimestamp [<host>]

crsctl query crs lastactivetimestamp [<host>]\\n     Lists the Last active timestamp of a leaf node.\\nwhere\\n     Default         Lists the last active timestamp of the local leaf node\\n     host            Lists the last active timestamp of the named leaf node
unable to get the last active timestamp
data.cause: The crsctl query failed because the last active timestamp could not\nbe retrieved. Either the clusterware stack was down, or the\nrequesting user was not root (UNIX) or Administrator (WINDOWS).
data.action: Bring up the clusterware stack using the command 'crsctl start crs'\nand retry the query or retry the query as a privileged user.

data.message: Last active timestamp query failed for node %s.
data.cause: The crsctl query failed to retrieve the last active timestamp for\nthe indicated node.
data.action: Examine the accompanying error message, address issues reported and\nretry the query.

data.message: The last active timestamp of node [%s] is [%s]\\n
Node %s is not a leaf node.
data.cause: An attempt to list the last active timestamp for the indicated node\nwas rejected because that node was not a leaf node.
data.action: Rerun the command from a leaf node or specifying a leaf node that\nis a cluster member or was a cluster member.

data.message: crsctl get cluster class\\n     Get the cluster class
Cluster class is '%s'
Node '%s' configured role is '%s', but active role is '%s'.
Node '%s' active role is '%s', but configured role is '%s'.
Restart Oracle High Availability Services for the new role to take effect.
insufficient permission to create or delete a member cluster configuration
data.cause: An attempt was made to create or delete a member cluster\nconfiguration by a user who was not an Oracle Grid Infrastructure\nuser.
data.action: Rerun the command as an Oracle Grid Infrastructure user.

data.message: The member cluster configuration must be run on a \\"Domain Services Cluster\\" only.
data.cause: An attempt was made to create a member cluster configuration on a\ncluster which is not a \\"Domain Services Cluster\\".
data.action: Rerun the command on a \\"Domain Services Cluster\\"."

data.message: crsctl get cluster configuration\\n    Displays the  cluster configuration information
Name      : %(1)s\\nClass     : %(2)s\\nType      : %(3)s\\n
failure getting the cluster configuration
data.cause: An attempt to get additional configuration information from\nthe Grid Infrastructure Management Respository (GIMR) failed.\nThis is an internal error.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: permission to retrieve the cluster configuration denied
data.cause: An attempt to retrieve the configuration failed because\nthe stack was down and permission to retrieve the\ncluster configuration with the stack down was denied.
data.action: Run the query when the Oracle Clusterware stack is up or\nas a privileged user such as root (on UNIX) or\nadministrator (on Windows).

data.message: failure getting the local node number from Cluster Synchronization Services (return code %d)
data.cause: An attempt to execute the command 'crsctl get node role status'\nfailed  because Cluster Synchronization Services (CSS)\nwas not running.
data.action: Ensure that the CSS daemon is running on this node, and then retry\nthe operation.

data.message: the active status role of node '%(1)s' is unknown
data.cause: An attempt to execute the command 'crsctl get node role status'\nfailed for the indicated node  because Cluster Synchronization\nServices (CSS) was not running.
data.action:
Ensure that CSS daemon is running on the indicated node, and
then retry the operation.

data.message: Brief Usage: crsrename cluster <new_clustername>
operation not supported for single-instance high availability configurations
data.cause: An attempt was made to execute a command to rename a cluster,\nwhich was not supported in the current single-instance high\navailability configuration.
data.action: None.

data.message: operation only supported for standalone cluster
data.cause: An attempt to rename a cluster was rejected because that operation\nwas only supported for standalone cluster configurations.
data.action: None.

data.message: successfully set the cluster name
failed to set the cluster name
data.cause: There was an internal error while setting the cluster name.
data.action: Contact Oracle Support Services.

data.message: cluster name is invalid
data.cause: An attempt to rename a cluster was rejected because an invalid\ncluster name was specified.
data.action:
Rerun the command with a valid cluster name. A valid cluster name
should be at least one character long but no more than 15 characters
in length. The cluster name consists of alphanumeric characters and
the hyphen (-) character (a..z,A..Z,0..9,-). It cannot begin or end
with the hyphen (-) character.

data.message: operation not supported for clusters where an RHP Server or an RHP Client is configured
data.cause: An attempt to rename a cluster was rejected because that operation\nwas not supported for clusters where an RHP Server or\nan RHP Client is configured.
data.action: None.

data.message: operation not supported for clusters where Quality of Service Management is configured and is in use
data.cause: An attempt to rename a cluster was rejected because that operation\nwas not supported for clusters where Quality of Service Management\nwas configured and was in use.
data.action: None.
